<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mich. Hoops Star Got Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Former Michigan basketball player Louis  
Bullock received more than $50,000 from a Detroit man who had been 
banned from contact with the basketball program, a newspaper 
reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources identified as being familiar with a federal  
investigation of Ed Martin told The Ann Arbor News that the booster 
loaned the money to Bullock in anticipation of being repaid with 
Bullock's future earnings as a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock, a guard, completed his four-year career in March as the  
Wolverines' third highest scorer. The Minnesota Timberwolves 
drafted him in the second round last June, then traded him to the 
Orlando Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, a retired Ford Motor Co. electrician, emerged in 1996 as  
the central figure as the university and the NCAA investigated 
allegations of rules violations and other improper conduct within 
the basketball program. 
</P>
<P>
	He was banned from contact with the program in March 1997. But  
sources told the News that most of the money Bullock was said to 
have received from Martin was paid afterward, during his junior and 
senior seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Louis Bullock has been interviewed by the federal authorities.  
He has cooperated completely with them,'' his attorney, Steven 
Fishman, said Thursday. ``I refuse to divulge any further details 
of what has been said, but I can assure you the subject of the 
interview had to do only with loans allegedly made by Mr. Martin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock himself would not comment on the allegations, Fishman  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Convertino -- investigating  
Martin's activities -- declined comment earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents are investigating  
whether Martin and his son, Carlton, were ringleaders of an 
extensive gambling operation at Ford plants. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials have said the FBI told them that no  
evidence of gambling on Wolverines games has been uncovered. 
</P>
<P>
	If the NCAA finds proof that Bullock took money from Martin  
after Martin was banned, the university could face another inquiry 
or further sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Tom Goss told the News that players were  
sternly reminded to avoid Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to make sure people are informed and to share with  
them ... that it will not be tolerated and it's unacceptable,'' 
Goss said. ``But if a person says, `I'm not doing (anything 
wrong),' you have to accept what they say.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
