<HEADLINE> Plane, Bodies Recovered in Virginia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Rescue crews today found three bodies near  
a small airplane that smashed into the rocky face of a mountain and 
were searching for a fourth person. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-seat Cessna 172 was found around 8:30 a.m., two days  
after it crashed. It was about 10 miles from its destination, the 
Shenandoah Valley Regional Airport at Weyers Cave, said Randy Frank 
of the Appalachian Search and Rescue Team. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff William Morris said the plane sheared the tops of trees  
and nosed into the side of a mountain, and the impact had ``an 
accordion effect'' on the aircraft. The cause of the crash had not 
been determined. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot of the plane was Robert Spencer, a 30-year-old  
volunteer firefighter and paramedic from Gloucester. Passengers 
were Cathy Turner, 38, and two children, his son and her daughter. 
Authorities did not immediately say which of the four was still 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer took off Wednesday morning from the Newport  
News-Williamsburg International Airport. He told Federal Aviation 
Administration controllers after takeoff that he was flying by 
visual flight rules and had not filed a flight plan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
