<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 11:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BellSouth Gives Away Some Web Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- As the competition for Internet customers  
intensifies globally, BellSouth has gone local with its Buzz Web 
site, a portal to scores of community Web pages that BellSouth 
gives away for free. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-state Internet service provider is adding to the 62  
community sites by offering free Web pages to any nonprofit 
organization that meets minimal requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize it is not our place in the market to compete with  
national companies like Yahoo,'' said Ted Creech, director of 
marketing and business for BellSouth Buzz, the company's Web 
service. ``We have created a portal that reflects our localness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Internet users who arrive at the BellSouth Buzz portal see a box  
that prompts them to choose one of 62 possible cities. Upon 
selecting the city, a BellSouth Buzz Web site specific to that city 
pops onto the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web site contains local news, calendars and discussion  
groups, plus national news, stocks, sports scores, weather and 
search engines. One site feature, Community Source, has links to 
the free community Web pages. 
</P>
<P>
	It's good advertising for BellSouth.  
</P>
<P>
	While anyone can log onto BellSouth Buzz without subscribing to  
the company's $19.95-a-month Internet service, the company hopes 
the local sites will draw more attention to BellSouth's services 
and grab more Internet customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounds like you're giving away a service, and that's  
inherently not what a corporation is looking for,'' Creech said. 
``Whenever an organization creates a free web (page), they're 
basically creating extra advertising space for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven North Carolina cities -- Arden, Asheville, Cape Hatteras,  
Chapel Hill, Charlotte, Durham, Greensboro, High Point, Raleigh, 
Wilmington and Winston-Salem -- can be accessed from BellSouth Buzz. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few nonprofit North Carolina groups have logged in a free  
Web page since the program began June 1, and the company wants to 
give away hundreds more. 
</P>
<P>
	So, two weeks ago, BellSouth hired Linda Anderson, a  
Charlotte-based employee who will try to convince local North 
Carolina organizations they could benefit from free Web exposure. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenda Scofield, executive director for the Western North  
Carolina HIV/AIDS Consortium in Asheville, took up BellSouth's 
offer as soon as one of her board members heard about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're non-profit, and we really have to watch our dollars,''  
Scofield said. ``We knew we wanted a Web page. We definitely would 
have discussed it a little more if it wasn't free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she's already seen results since the page was posted a  
few months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have gotten calls about it, people e-mailing us from it,''  
Scofield said. ``We've actually had someone contact us from out of 
state about our services because he was moving here. It has made an 
impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Requirements for the free page are minimal, Creech said  
Thursday. The organization need not be a federally recognized 
nonprofit, but only show it doesn't plan to sell or promote goods 
and services through the Web site for a profit. School groups, 
local clubs and governmental organizations would be eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Once approved for a Web page, an organization can create its own  
page by following online instructions, using one of five 
BellSouth-provided templates. It can add its own graphics and 
photos. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sites are very easy to build. You don't need to know any  
code or HTML,'' said Tim Hart, community manager for BellSouth 
Buzz. Hart oversees the 12 employees, like Linda, who add new Web 
pages. 
</P>
<P>
	Company representative Sue Holub said the sites have hometown  
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to go to the Yahoo search engine, but who cares  
what's going on in Boise, Idaho, if you live in Raleigh, North 
Carolina?'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Web site is http://buzz.bellsouth.net  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
