<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Suspect on Bus Day Earlier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A man charged with stabbing three people on an  
Amtrak train had been removed from a bus by Illinois State Police a 
day earlier after complaining that other passengers were 
threatening him with a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	When the officers searched Aaron Hall for weapons, they found a  
pocketknife with a 2 1/2-inch blade, Illinois State Police Master Sgt. 
Lincoln Hampton said. Police believe the same weapon was later used 
in Thursday's attack on the train. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, 41, of Ontario, Calif., is accused of stabbing two  
conductors and a passenger as they tried to subdue him on the Lake 
Shore Limited run from Chicago to New York. Two of the men remained 
hospitalized Friday but were recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	The train was near Cleveland when the attacks occurred.  
Authorities said Hall claimed he acted in self-defense and that a 
porter had threatened him with a gun. No gun was found on either 
the train or the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall is being held in Ohio on three counts of attempted murder.  
His appointed attorney, Gerald Piszczek, was unavailable to comment 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was harmed on the Greyhound bus, which was near  
Princeton, Ill., about 100 miles west of Chicago, when the 
disturbance began Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police allowed Hall to keep the pocketknife because carrying a  
small pocketknife is legal. The driver still asked that Hall be 
removed, and another bus took him to Chicago where he boarded the 
train, Olmsted Township Patrolman Matthew Vanyo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hampton said Hall had boarded the bus in Iowa and was headed to  
Chicago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
