<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 16:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene, Miller Take 200M Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Maurice Greene did his best imitation of  
Carl Lewis. Inger Miller did her best imitation of Marion Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	By doing so, the two training partners won the 200-meter dashes  
at the World Championships Friday night, giving the United States a 
sweep of the short sprints. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, winner of the 100-meter title earlier, became the first  
sprinter to win the 100 and 200 at a major global meet since Lewis 
swept both at the 1984 Olympics. His time was a season-best 19.90 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller outshone the more renowned Jones, winner of the 100 who  
was missing in the 200 after pulling up in the semifinals with back 
spasms and cramps, winning in 21.77. It was the world's fastest 
time this year and the best of her career. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, the two teammates embraced warmly, with both in  
tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inger and me got very close this week,'' Greene said. ``We  
came here to do a job. She stood by me when I won the 100. We 
achieved what we came here to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The emotional Greene also embraced his coach, John Smith, and  
manager Emmanuel Hudson, and was hugged by the championships' 
mascot, dressed in a green cartoon costume. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene then was handed a bag of T-shirts bearing his picture and  
his nickname, ``phonoMOnon.'' As he took his victory lap around the 
track, he tossed the shirts into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene had a couple of other emotional moments. The first was on  
the victory stand, where he broke down during the national anthem. 
``Those were tears of joy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene also cried on the podium in 1997 when he won his first  
100 title. He was even more emotional this time ``because for me to 
come here and win the 100 was great, but to try something I had 
never done before (the double) and put my body in a place it's 
never been before was exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second time Greene became emotional Friday was in the  
interview room. ``I'm still crying inside,'' he said. ``This is 
something I've been dreaming of as a child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he treasured his 200 gold more than the 100 because it  
was his first at that distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``After I saw Inger win, I knew I had to go out there and do it  
for the team,'' Greene said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene was helped by the absence of two of the world's top  
sprinters. His teammate, Ato Boldon, the 1997 world champion, and 
Namibia's Frankie Fredericks, the Olympic silver medalist in the 
100 and 200, were both out with injuries. Fredericks made the final 
but withdrew with a nerve injury in his left hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller showed her emotions on the track. When she realized she  
was the winner, she rotated her hands back and forth like a boxer, 
then lay down on the track and went into a series of bicycle kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't expect to run that fast,'' Miller said after lowering  
her personal record by .33 seconds. ``My goal was to win gold, and 
I did that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I ran an exceptional PR. I looked first to make sure it  
was me. It's unbelievable. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a one-woman show anymore.''  
</P>
<P>
	That was a reference to Jones, who had dominated the sprints  
until she was injured. Jones was No. 1 in the world in both the 100 
and 200 last year, and had the fastest times this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller showed she was coming on fast in the 100 at the World  
Championships, running three PRs, including 10.79 in earning the 
silver medal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think she made any mistakes,'' Greene said about  
Miller's 200. ``She was phenomenal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen what she's been through. She had to leave her  
father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was coached by her father, Lennox, the 1968 Olympic  
silver medalist and the 1972 bronze medalist in the 100 while 
representing Jamaica. His daughter won a gold in the 400 relay at 
the 1996 Atlanta Games, making them the first father-daughter 
Olympic medalists in track and field. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller decided last year to join the Smith group, which also  
includes Boldon and sprinter Jon Drummond. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father and I made the decision together,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity to train with these guys was exciting, but I  
had to carry my weight. Basically, I'm the only woman on the 
circuit with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said she stumbled early in the race but quicklly  
recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard John's voice inside me saying, `Do it, do it, do it,'  
'' she said, referring to Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference now is atmosphere and intensity. Before, I used  
to train by myself. Now I train with these guys and it's fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's other finals, Italy's Fabrizio Mori, who was at  
first disqualified in the semifinals of the men's 400 hurdles and 
then reinstated, won in 47.72, the world's fastest time this year; 
Romania's Gabriela Szabo retained the women's 5,000 title at 
14:41.82, a championship record, and Hongyu Liu led a 1-2 Chinese 
finish in the women's 20-kilometer walk at 1:30:50. 
</P>
<P>
	Mori's victory was protested by the French team, which claimed  
the Italian ran out of his lane and should have been disqualified. 
The protest was rejected. Had it been accepted, France's Stephane 
Diagana, the second-place finisher and Olympic champion, would have 
been the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Ludmila Engquist, the inspirational story of the  
championships, continued her remarkable run toward a second 
straight title in the women's 100 hurdles. Engquist, who had 
undergone four chemotherapy treatments for breast cancer and has 
two more remaining, won her semifinal heat at 12.50, the 
second-fastest in the world for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The emotional Engquist collapsed into tears when she saw the  
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Gail Devers, the 1993 and 1995 champion, won the other semifinal  
at 12.70. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
