<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Eases Out of Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- After struggling through its deepest recession  
in years, Hong Kong's economy started growing again in the spring, 
the government said Friday, offering a fresh signal that Asia is 
recovering from its financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The return to growth -- an increase of 0.5 percent in the second  
quarter -- was a far cry from the economic booms that converted Hong 
Kong into one of the most congested and expensive cities on earth, 
but a welcome relief to officials who had been looking for an end 
to the economic contraction. 
</P>
<P>
	The GDP numbers for the three months ending June 30 surpassed  
the expectations of private economists who had been predicting 
further shrinkage of 1 percent to 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Another struggling Asian country, the Philippines, also had  
promising news Friday, as the government announced 
greater-than-expected economic growth during the second quarter. 
The country's GDP rose 3.6 percent, boosted by strong gains in 
agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang proclaimed a  
``very robust recovery'' and predicted the economy can keep 
expanding. 
</P>
<P>
	The GDP figures, which represent the value of Hong Kong's  
production and services, were up by 0.5 percent when compared with 
the second quarter of 1998, but on a seasonally adjusted 
quarter-to-quarter basis, they represented growth of about 3 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, officials cautioned the early signs of growth were  
fragile and more troubles could develop. The outlook remains 
clouded by various uncertainties. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time officials were announcing the territory had  
pulled out of recession, Hong Kong banks raised interest rates by a 
quarter point, in a move that followed the U.S. Federal Reserve but 
could hinder recovery prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic bust sent Hong Kong's unemployment to record highs,  
devastated the crucial property market and threw consumer prices 
into a spooky downward spiral of deflation that economists predict 
won't go away any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Hong Kong people voiced doubts Friday evening about the  
pace of recovery from the 15-month recession that cast a shadow 
over the former British colony in its first two years under Chinese 
sovereignty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hong Kong's recovery will be very slow, maybe one or two  
years, but the Hong Kong people are very hard and very 
intelligent,'' said Terence Li, sales manager of a Chinese hotel 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Others agree it will take time before well-heeled Hong Kong  
people are confident enough to go back to their free-spending ways 
on the fanciest French wines, luxury cars and wallet-busting dinner 
banquets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not see a return to the happy days -- not until mid  
2000,'' said William Lau, a Jaguar automobile dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hard times forced Hong Kong to seek new ways to build a better  
future, including proposals to lure more high-tech firms to the 
territory, a plan to turn Hong Kong into a global center for 
Chinese and herbal medicines and negotiations about building a 
Disney theme park to lure more tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong has seen much of its industrial base crumble as its  
old manufacturing jobs were moved to cheaper locations in mainland 
China, although it is a huge banking and shipping center and 
retains a vital role as a conduit for Chinese exports to the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the rebound was attributed to a rise in exports, but  
they could run into troubles depending on economic conditions in 
key markets: the United States, Japan and Europe, government 
economist K.Y. Tang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions in the Taiwan Strait, as China and Taiwan square off  
over Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui's recent affirmation of 
statehood, could also aggravate Hong Kong's effort to recover. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
