<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prozac Advocate Gets License Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WENATCHEE, Wash. (AP) -- A psychologist dubbed the ``pied piper  
of Prozac'' for his aggressive promotion of the antidepressant has 
temporarily regained the right to practice, two months after it was 
stripped by a state licensing board. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the board yanked James Goodwin's license, accusing him  
of failing to comply with the terms of a 1996 disciplinary order. 
</P>
<P>
	But Thursday, a judge gave it back, at least temporarily, until  
Goodwin's appeal of the Examining Board of Psychology's 10-year 
revocation of his license is decided this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Chelan County Superior Court Judge John E. Bridges also said he  
expected Goodwin to win that appeal, which will be heard by another 
judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm relieved,'' Goodwin said after the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin first made a name for himself in the early 1990s in a  
rash of media appearances advocating the benefits of 
antidepressants, such as Prozac and Paxil. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin takes medication for his own depressive illness. He  
antagonized licensing board members by suggesting some of them were 
mentally ill and could use it as well. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Goodwin sent a packet of information to the board  
with a photocopy of his left hand, middle finger extended. He later 
it was merely a physical illustration of part of his therapy, he 
said, where fingers are used to represent self and self's 
relationship to others. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the board accused him of breaching patient  
confidentiality, diagnosing patients without adequate evaluation, 
pressuring patients into taking Prozac and retaliating against a 
psychologist who protested his treatment methods. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were settled in 1996, with Goodwin required to enter  
into a contract with an adviser to review patient diagnoses for as 
long as three years. He refused, saying the contract imposed other 
restrictions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
