<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track World Championships Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- A relay anchor leg by world record-holder  
Michael Johnson will cap the World Championships on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who set the world 400-meter record of 43.18 seconds  
Thursday night and owns the 200 world record of 19.32 from the 1996 
Olympic Games, will run the final leg on the U.S. 1,600-meter relay 
team, the final event of the championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson might even run in Saturday's semifinals.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've spoken to the U.S. coaches,'' Johnson said Friday. ``If  
they need me in the preliminary, I will run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Americans win, Johnson would pick up his ninth career  
World Championships gold medal, more than any other athlete in 
history. Johnson's record-setting 400 victory here gave him his 
eighth gold, tying him with Carl Lewis atop the all-time list. 
</P>
<P>
	The other 1,600 relay runners will come from a pool that  
includes quarter-milers Antonio Pettigrew, Danny McCray and Jerome 
Davis, and hurdlers Joey Woody and Angelo Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	Woody was a last-minute addition to the group, replacing the  
injured Jerome Young. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. men's coach George Williams also has a six-man pool for the  
400 relay, but said Friday he will run Jon Drummond, Tim 
Montgomery, Brian Lewis and 100-meter world record holder and 
two-time world champion Maurice Greene in the final in that order. 
</P>
<P>
	The others on the team are Tim Harden and Tony McCall.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. women's coach Lance Harter's plans were scrambled when  
100-meter champion Marion Jones was injured during the 200 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	That left him with Gail Devers, Inger Miller, Nanceen Perry,  
Cheryl Taplin, Andrea Anderson and hurdler Miesha McKelvey for the 
400 relay pool, and Anderson, Jearl Miles-Clark, Maicel Malone, 
Michelle Collins and Suziann Reid for the 1,600 relay. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HIGHLY RATED:* Michael Johnson's drawing power in Europe is as  
impressive as his speed on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-two percent of the British television viewing audience  
tuned in to the BBC Thursday night to watch Johnson shatter the 
oldest existing men's track mark. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was pointed out to Johnson that his record race wasn't  
shown on live television in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just glad my fans can see it (on tape),'' Johnson said.  
``We're just not to the point in the U.S. where we are worthy of 
live television. Hopefully last night's race will help change 
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BBC figures showed 8.6 million Britons saw Johnson's 400 final,  
500,000 more people than the peak viewing audience for this year's 
Wimbledon men's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson also outdrew Wednesday's 110-meter high hurdles final in  
which Colin Jackson earned Britain's first gold medal at a global 
championships since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the Grand National, the annual horse jumping race which  
registered a peak viewing audience of 10.1 million, has attracted 
more viewers on BBC television for a 1999 sports event broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ON YOUR MARKS, GET BLESSED, GO:* The first marathon of the new  
century will start at noon on Jan. 1, 2000, in Vatican City. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF Rome Millennium Marathon was conceived to ``carry  
through the streets of Rome and throughout the world a message of 
peace and brotherhood,'' International Amateur Athletics Federation 
president Primo Nebiolo said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pope John Paul II will provide a pre-race blessing, Nebiolo  
said, and St. Peter's Cathedral will be the backdrop at the 
starting line. 
</P>
<P>
	The finish location has not been decided yet, Enrico Castrucci,  
head of the marathon's organizing committee said, but it likely 
will be near the Colosseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebiolo said he hopes to attract 50,000 entrants, including at  
least one from each of the 210 IAAF member countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
