<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 10:18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Violence in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- More violence broke out in East Timor  
today, despite angry U.N. demands that the government rein in 
militiamen who don't want the territory to break away from 
Indonesia. A vote on independence is set for Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	About 800 militiamen attacked the village of Memo, near the  
militia-controlled town of Maliana. Earlier, pro-independence 
supporters clashed with a smaller group of paramilitaries driving 
through the village. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said two people were stabbed to death by the  
militiamen. Another was shot dead. KIPER, a local monitoring 
agency, said nine houses were burned before the villagers took 
revenge and burned cars carrying the assailants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ready and waiting for them,'' villager Anacleto Lopes  
said. ``We have been told they are coming in to attack us and we 
will fight them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The attack came one day after a rampage in Dili, the provincial  
capital, that left six people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.N. mission chief Ian Martin said today that neither  
incident will dissuade the United Nations from going ahead with 
Monday's election. 
</P>
<P>
	Many more were injured Thursday after militiamen who oppose East  
Timor becoming independent from Indonesia swept through Dili and 
fired shots at crowds of pro-independence supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said police did nothing to stop the gun-toting  
militiamen and even helped them. In response, Martin warned that 
the world will be watching Indonesia during the vote, and there 
will be ``serious consequences'' if the government doesn't 
dramatically improve security immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have not responded to the accusations.  
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, military commander Gen. Wiranto said he has ordered  
Indonesian police to capture anyone who incites violence. He called 
on both sides to hand over their guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police are ready to safeguard the implementation of the  
ballot, and take action without discrimination,'' said Wiranto, 
who, like many Indonesians, uses one name. ``We have no intention 
to delay or to lengthen the preparation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plebiscite will give East Timorese a choice between staying  
part of Indonesia as an autonomous region or becoming fully 
independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the escalating violence appeared designed to frighten  
independence supporters away from the poll, Martin believed East 
Timorese would show ``courage and determination to exercise their 
democratic rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The militia were carrying guns, weapons. And once again,  
heavily armed and equipped police failed to intervene when that 
militia violence was carried on in front of them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged Indonesia  
to ``control the militias, who it is increasingly clear, are intent 
on disrupting the popular consultation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dili was quiet today. Many shops and offices were closed and  
most residents stayed off the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, jailed East Timor separatist leader Jose Alexandre  
``Xanana'' Gusmao, called on his guerrillas not to launch 
counterattacks against anti-independence gangs. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead he pleaded for the United Nations to deploy armed  
peacekeepers to replace unarmed police advisers and military 
observers stationed across the half-island territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appeal to the U.N. Security Council for an immediate  
deployment of a peace enforcement force in East Timor,'' he said in 
a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations has resisted calls to send peacekeepers.  
Instead, the Security Council is expected today to nearly double 
the number of police advisers and increase the number of military 
liaisons by six times. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusmao condemned Indonesia for breaking a U.N. agreement to  
guarantee law and order before and after the ballot. He accused 
Wiranto of being behind the violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia, he said, ``is clearly demonstrating that not only  
does it not want peace in East Timor, but it is intent on pursuing 
a strategy of instability and chaos in the territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia has said that Gusmao, who is now under house arrest,  
will be released on Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975,  
triggering years of guerrilla warfare and human rights abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-Indonesian leaders have warned that a civil war could erupt  
if East Timor becomes independent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
