<DOCNO> APW19990827.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 02:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. May Put First Woman on Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Margaret Marshall, a South African immigrant who  
has served on the state Supreme Judicial Court for three years, has 
been nominated to be the first female chief justice in its 307-year 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Paul Cellucci announced her nomination Thursday. She would  
succeed Chief Justice Herbert Wilkins, who retires this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Her appointment must be approved by the eight-member Governor's  
Council. Cellucci said he hopes the council approves the 
appointment before Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her outstanding intellect, her personal integrity and skills  
as a consensus builder make her an ideal person'' for the job, 
Cellucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall, 54, said she was ``deeply honored'' and recognized the  
``unique place of the Supreme Judicial Court in our nation, and 
beyond our borders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court has been around since 1692.  
</P>
<P>
	Marshall, only the second woman on the court, is a graduate of  
Harvard University and Yale Law School. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall graduated from Witwatersrand University in Johannesburg  
in 1966, emigrating to the United States two years later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rookie Sets Pace in IRL Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOUNTAIN, Colo. (AP) -- Two months after nearly winning here  
despite crippling injuries, rookie Scott Harrington served notice 
again, posting the fastest times in both practice sessions Friday 
for the Colorado Indy 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, threatening to scramble the Indy Racing League's  
tightly bunched driver standings, turned a lap of 175.234 mph in 
the morning session on Pikes Peak International Raceway's one-mile 
oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Schmidt was next at 173.972 mph and Jeff Ward at 173.871.  
</P>
<P>
	In the afternoon, Harrington went 174.258 mph, bettering Robby  
McGehee, at 172.538 and Ward at 172.166. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying was scheduled for Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Scott Goodyear leads the driver standings with 193 points, but  
eight are within 50 points, which is what the winner of Sunday's 
race will receive. The contenders include Greg Ray, who has won two 
of the last three IRL races, with 191 points, and Kenny Brack with 
179. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear, Ray and Brack posted modest practice speeds on Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	``The way the point structure is, it changes so drastically, so  
quickly,'' said Ray, who won the June race here. ``One guy can have 
a bad weekend and he can go from second to eighth. Or you can go 
from sixth to first real quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The three of us might wind up in the infield on Sunday,''  
Goodyear noted, ``and it might be three different people you're 
looking at at Texas,'' the final race on Oct. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago on this track, Harrington was poised for a  
top-three finish -- and possibly a victory -- when he brushed the 
wall with 17 laps to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were reeling in Sam (runnerup finisher Schmidt) and Greg,''  
Harrington recalled. ``I feel like we should have won that one. I 
definitely feel we let that one get away from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He challenged for the lead despite driving with a broken right  
leg, torn ligaments in his left knee and three cracked ribs as a 
result of a crash two weeks earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Harrington still wore a brace on his left knee, but  
said he was significantly improved. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically, I'm way better,'' he said. ``Probably the biggest  
thing I'm dealing with now is the physical conditioning. I had a 
pretty regular routine of working out. Then I had injuries to both 
legs, and the ribs prevented me from doing much upper-body work. 
The conditioning definitely has suffered, but in the last four 
weeks I've been able to do a lot more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His car, meanwhile, remains in superb condition.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're using pretty much the same setup we had in June,'' he  
said. ``Very minor changes. This afternoon, we got close to where 
we were this morning. We figured we knew what we needed to know so 
we decided to park it and skip the last part of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just got a great race car this weekend. This is  
definitely the fastest car we've had all year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, 35, of Indianapolis, admitted that his team remains  
basically a shoestring operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've run one engine since Charlotte (May 1),'' he said. ``We  
rebuild it every weekend. It's kind of hard for us to practice pit 
stops because we only have two guys who work for us. The rest of 
the guys are volunteers and weekend help. It's hard for me to sit 
in the car and plug the air jack in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Kite lost an engine during the morning session and didn't  
practice in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyce Carlson caused heavy damage to the rear of his car when he  
hit the wall in Turn 4. Carlson wasn't hurt, and he turned several 
laps in his backup car in the afternoon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
