<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Meets Iraq Inspector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke met Friday with the  
acting chief U.N. weapons inspector for Iraq, familiarizing himself 
with one of the most contentious issues he'll face as America's new 
U.N. ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke spent about a half an hour with Charles Duelfer,  
acting head of the U.N. Special Commission, to discuss the stalled 
process of disarming Iraq of its banned weapons, a U.S. official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was paying another round of courtesy calls to the  
Security Council president before flying to the Balkans for a 
whirlwind tour of U.S., NATO and U.N. operations. He is expected to 
take the U.S. seat in the council chamber on Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	In a meeting Friday with this month's president of the Security  
Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, and Namibia's Foreign Minister 
Theo-Ben Gurirab, who will be president of the next U.N. General 
Assembly session in September, Holbrooke promised to make Africa 
one of his priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look forward to working with both of you,'' Holbrooke told  
the two. ``Working on the issues of Africa here in New York will be 
one of my ... top priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the two days since he was sworn in, Holbrooke has been paying  
courtesy calls to U.N. officials and meeting with staff at the U.S. 
Mission to the United Nations. 
</P>
