<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Under Fire for Russian Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House cast it as standard operating  
procedure: Top administration officials, including Vice President 
Al Gore, were not told of a Justice Department investigation into 
allegations of Russian money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Standard or not, the lack of knowledge left Gore vulnerable to  
criticism by his Republican rivals in the 2000 presidential 
campaign. Steve Forbes' campaign taped radio ads on Friday, 
criticizing Gore as ``out of the loop'' and insisting he owes 
American taxpayers an apology. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long-standing practice that law enforcement authorities  
make the judgment about when to brief the national security team,'' 
White House spokesman David Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno and national security officials at  
the White House were not briefed until Thursday and Friday on the 
investigation into accusations that Russian mobsters and 
politicians laundered money, possibly including diverted U.S. funds 
from the International Monetary Fund, through accounts at the Bank 
of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually such briefing decisions are based on a determination of  
political or foreign-policy consequences. This one was made because 
of press interest stirred by Gore's rivals, said one administration 
official. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president and his aides have long spoken of Gore's  
unique and hands-on role in U.S.-Russia diplomacy, particularly as 
chairman of a joint commission on bilateral ties with former 
Russian prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	As for U.S. policy, Gore and other administration officials have  
a record of pressing Russia to crack down on corruption and 
implement economic reforms as a condition of continued aid from the 
IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to make clear that Russia must have the  
credibility and fairness and strong mechanisms to prevent this kind 
of financial crime,'' said Leavy. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole circulated a statement  
to reporters on Friday saying that Gore ``has failed in his only 
major foreign policy effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``After seven years of his foreign policy stewardship and  
cultivation of Moscow's 'revolving door' leadership, Russian 
organized crime is threatening the social fabric of Russia,'' Dole 
said. ``The Dole administration will take this issue on directly 
with (Russian President Boris) Yeltsin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes was airing his radio ads on stations serving President  
Clinton's next vacation stop, Skaneateles Lake in upstate New York, 
a hub for national political reporters during the president's stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing reports of Russian corruption, Forbes said Gore should  
apologize to the Russian people and American taxpayers for the 
``economic and political time bomb'' in Russia. ``Vice President 
Gore co-chairs the commission which oversees U.S.-Russian 
relations, but his aides say he was out of the loop,'' read the 
script of Forbes' ad. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes called for an immediate halt to all foreign aid to Russia  
until officials have rooted out ``the corruption of Russia's robber 
barons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the vice president and his family summering on a North  
Carolina island, and his campaign and White House offices emptied 
of vacationing aides, press inquiries were referred to Leavy, 
President Clinton's national security spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Gore spokeswoman Jodi Sakol: ``The vice president will not  
have a statement until he has more facts.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
