<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ARM CEO Martin Ruby Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Martin H. Ruby, chief executive and  
chairman of ARM Financial Group Inc., resigned Friday from the 
company he helped form six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruby's resignation comes a few weeks after the company reported  
$174 million in second-quarter net losses, a drop of $7.30 per 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Three class-action lawsuits were filed last week alleging the  
Louisville-based company misrepresented or omitted information 
about its financial condition, artificially inflating the value of 
its stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruby, 49, could not be reached for comment Friday. A spokesman  
for the company called his resignation ``a mutually agreed upon 
decision between him and the board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following his resignation, the board created a three-member  
``office of the president'' to oversee operations consisting of 
John R. Lindholm, president, retail business division; John R. 
McGeeny, executive vice president, general council; and William H. 
Panning, executive vice president and chief investment officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruby helped found the company in 1993.  
</P>
<P>
	ARM Financial sells guaranteed investment contracts to  
institutions and annuities and other retirement savings products to 
individuals and employs 300 people. Among its subsidiaries are 
Integrity Life Insurance Co. and National Integrity Life Insurance 
Co. 



  	   	
</P>
