<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Sisters Ready for Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When they first showed up to play for pay,  
sisters Venus and Serena Williams were quick to state their goal: 
They would be No. 1 in women's tennis -- or No. 1 and 1a. 
</P>
<P>
	They had plenty of confidence, even though they lacked  
experience. And their upfront attitude didn't always go down easy 
with the other players. 
</P>
<P>
	It almost seemed too easy when Venus reached the U.S. Open final  
in her debut in the tournament in 1997. Then reality set in -- for 
her opponents. She was that good. 
</P>
<P>
	And if that wasn't enough, along came baby sister Serena. Their  
father, Richard Williams, who taught her daughters how to play, 
proclaimed that Serena would be the better of the two. 
</P>
<P>
	In just the 13th and 14th matches of her professional career,  
she defeated two players ranked in the Top 10. And last year, the 
5-foot-10 right-hander had the fifth fastest women's serve at 
Flushing Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	When the U.S. Open begins its two-week run at the National  
Tennis Center on Monday, the 19-year-old Venus will be playing in 
America's premier tennis tournament for the third time. Serena, 17, 
will be making her second appearance on the hard courts in Flushing 
Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	And they would love to play each other in Arthur Ashe Stadium.  
</P>
<P>
	That, however, can only happen in the singles final because the  
third-seeded Venus is in the top half of the draw while Serena, 
seeded seventh, is in the bottom half. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, neither sister would be surprised if it happened.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked if she felt she could be No. 1, Venus recently said:  
</P>
<P>
	``Should I say `yes?' I'm not thinking about everyone else. I  
don't even know who's out there. My game's improving. I'm getting 
older and stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I'm at my best, I make important shots. I improvise. I  
make shots that my opponent thinks I shouldn't be able to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike two years ago, it wouldn't surprise many if Venus was  
playing on ``Super Saturday'' in two weeks when the women's title 
match will be sandwiched between the two men's semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	She has won four tournaments this year, two fewer than  
top-seeded Martina Hingis and the same as defending champion 
Lindsay Davenport, who is seeded second. Serena has three titles on 
her resume, all this year, and beat Hingis handily on hard courts 
in Key Biscayne, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was always a step faster and quicker than me,'' Hingis  
said of Serena. ``I was all of a sudden just standing there, didn't 
know what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After beating Hingis, Serena ran into Venus, whom she's never  
beaten. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the same player I was last year,'' Serena said. ``I've  
worked really hard to improve some things and get better. And it's 
showing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serena beat Hingis again in the Acura Classic in Los Angeles and  
won the event by stopping Julie Halard-Decugis in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was unbelievable,'' Halard-Decugis said. ``She is  
improving a lot. She played like No. 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serena isn't there yet, but it's her foremost goal.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm definitely trying to be the best I can be and that's the  
top spot,'' she said. ``I'm pretty serious about that. I definitely 
feel it's in reach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sisters have not played in the same tournament since Key  
Biscayne -- until now. If they do meet in the final, it will be only 
the 10th time in history that sisters have faced each other in 
singles in the U.S. championships. None of those matches has been 
after the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Venus will take on a qualifier in her first-round match, while  
Serena will face Kimberly Po of Rolling Hills, Calif. Po won their 
only other meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis will open against Kveta Hrdlickova of the Czech Republic  
and Davenport begins the defense of her crown against Corina 
Morariu of Boca Raton, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	One major player who will be missing is Steffi Graf, a five-time  
U.S. Open champion. After winning the French Open in June and 
reaching the final at Wimbledon, where she lost to Davenport, Graf 
retired, saying she had lost her desire to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis, who won the Australian Open in January for the third  
straight year, fell apart after losing the French Open title match 
to Graf, then was shocked in the first round at Wimbledon by 
Australia's Jelena Dokic. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 18-year-old Swiss right-hander is back on the right  
track, winning the du Maurier Open, a U.S. Open warmup event. 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport, somewhat of a surprise when she won a year ago, added  
the Wimbledon crown earlier this summer. And while she hasn't 
dominated the hard court circuit this year as she did in 1998, she 
comes into the Open full of confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	And confidence is something the Williams sisters know all about.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
