<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Autodesk Laying Off 350 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP ) -- Autodesk, the maker of design  
software for architects and engineers, is laying off about 350 
workers, or 10 percent of its work force, after reporting a 99 
percent plunge in second-quarter earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock in the world's fourth-largest PC software firm has lost  
about half its value since January amid declining demand from 
customers who have focused their spending on Internet initiatives 
and Y2K preparedness. 
</P>
<P>
	Autodesk stock fell another 5 percent Friday, closing at $23  
9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Income for the quarter was 1 cent per share, or about $400,000,  
Autodesk announced Thursday. The company had posted a 46 cent per 
share profit, or $27.5 million, in the same quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of our financial results, the actions announced  
today, while painful, are necessary to recalibrate the business and 
move forward with our strategic direction,'' Autodesk president and 
CEO Carol Bartz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts, which include 150 jobs in the firm's San Rafael and  
San Francisco offices, will create a leaner company focused on its 
main software business and developing Internet-based products and 
services, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are mindful that our customers are working in an  
increasingly Web-centric world and that means they have to be able 
to actively be involved in a Web-based environment,'' Ms. Bartz 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't been oblivious to the Internet,'' Bartz said. ``We  
know that the kind of design our customers do isn't really an 
Internet-biased product. But, yes, it's true we could have had an 
Internet aura around the products some quarters ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Software upgrades aren't a priority for many firms right now,  
says Jennifer M. Smith, a software analyst at Dean Rauscher Wessels 
in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies are saying I have to get a Web page, a Web strategy.  
That, combined with Y2K, people are saying that if I dont have to 
buy it now, Ill wait.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
