<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Gold Rises in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was down against most other major  
currencies in European trading Friday. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0473 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0451 Thursday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0469. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 111.62 Japanese yen, down from 111.70; 1.5288 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.5319; 1.4942 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.5010. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5876, down from $1.5890.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 111.57 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.5884. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8675 German marks, down from 1.8714; 
6.2633 French francs, down from 6.2765; 2.1042 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1086; 1,848.82 Italian lire, down from 1,852.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold in London was quoted at $253.80 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$253.60 on Thursday. In Zurich, gold closed at $253.65, up from 
$253.25. Gold rose $1.20 in Hong Kong to close at $254.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver in London was quoted at $5.08 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.07. 
</P>
