<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended the week lower  
Friday, with many investors taking profits on the back of an 
overnight slump on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell to  
66.92 points, or 0.38 percent, at 17,599.37 points. On Thursday, 
the average closed down 188.87 points, or 1.06 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average closed lower amid worries that domestic  
investors could start selling ahead of the end of the first half of 
the fiscal year on Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the small rebound in the U.S. dollar against the Japanese  
yen kept the stock market higher much of Friday. An overly strong 
yen tends to hurt Japanese companies that count on exports for 
profit. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also got a lift from news that spending by Japanese  
wage earners in July was up 2.6 percent in real terms from a year 
earlier. Economists had estimated that spending would rise 0.4 
percent from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar was quoted at 111.44 yen by late  
afternoon, up 0.38 yen from its level of 111.06 yen late Thursday 
in Tokyo but below its late New York level of 111.54 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks slumped on profit-taking following the fall on  
Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average fell 127.59 
points to 11,198.45 at Thursday's close after setting a record high 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 225.25 points, or 1.67 percent, closing at 
13,383.13. On Thursday, the index gained 129.25 points, or 1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong shares also fell on expectations of a rise in local  
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, Hong Kong banks announced after the closure of the  
market that they were raising their best lending rates to 8.50 
percent from 8.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks also raised their savings deposit rate by a quarter  
point to 3.75 percent in a move to match a quarter-point rate rise 
by the U.S. Federal Reserve earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was thin as many investors stayed on the sidelines to  
await government data on Hong Kong's economic growth in the second 
quarter. The government announced later that the territory's 
economy grew by 0.5 percent in the second quarter, pulling out of a 
drawn-out recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine stocks fell as investors ignored better-than-expected  
second quarter economic data and focused instead on a possible 
increase in domestic interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine Stock Exchange Index of 30 selected companies  
dropped 15.47 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,221.24. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine government announced Friday that the nation's  
gross national product expanded 3.8 percent and the gross domestic 
product grew 3.6 percent in the second quarter, largely because of 
improved agricultural production and a rejuvenated manufacturing 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower for the second consecutive  
session as Thursday losses in U.S. stock markets damped sentiment. 
The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 43.60 points, or 
0.5 percent, to 8,053.97. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed lower on concerns over a  
fee-payment scandal involving Bank Bali and the ruling political 
party, and instability in Ambon and Aceh provinces and East Timor. 
The Composite Index fell 1.5 percent, or or 8.846 points, to 
572.667. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 2.72 points, or 0.12 percent, to 
2,147.37. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed broadly lower, with  
losses across mining and energy stocks largely outpacing those in 
other industry groups. The All Ordinaries Index closed at 3,020.2, 
down 25.9 points, or 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed. The main Korea Composite Stock  
Price Index edged up 0.40 point to 960.28. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower. The Singapore Straits  
Times Index fell 7.91 points, or 0.3 percent, to 2,154.63. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher in thin  
trading. The main Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, rose 3.04 points, or 0.4 percent, to 764.79. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed slightly higher. The SET index  
rose 1.47 points, 0.3 percent, to 457.54. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
