<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Amish Released From Iowa Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDEPENDENCE, Iowa (AP) -- Four Amish inmates jailed for  
vandalizing a neighbor's farm were released early in part because 
officials feared they were being spoiled by modern conveniences 
such as plumbing and electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we better get them out of here because they were  
getting too used to it,'' said Buchanan County jail administrator 
Russell West. ``I think we were ruining them here. 
</P>
<P>
	``The TV, the electric light, telephone and running water -- I  
think they were starting to like it here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The four pleaded guilty to third-degree criminal mischief and  
were sentenced in May to 90 days in jail. They were released Aug. 
19 after serving 72 days. 
</P>
<P>
	About 400 of Hazleton's 700 residents are Amish -- the  
second-largest Old Order settlement in Iowa. Hazleton is about 20 
miles west of Waterloo. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Order Amish families have no electricity, no telephones and  
no other modern conveniences. They ride horse-drawn buggies instead 
of automobiles and scorn snaps or zippers in their clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolyn Kauffman, Andy Herschberger, William Gingerich -- all 19  
-- and 18-year-old Vernon Detweiler vandalized buildings and 
equipment early March 15 at the farm of Roman Raber. 
</P>
<P>
	The inmates were part of a group of young Amish who apparently  
thought Raber had told authorities about an underage drinking party 
that evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's deputies said windows and doors were broken, two  
buggies were overturned and smashed, and curtains, antiques and 
other items in the house were damaged as the Raber family huddled 
in fear inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The four showed no such rowdiness while in jail, leaving each  
weekday for work-release programs and on Sunday to attend church. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hardly knew they were here,'' West said. ``They never  
complained, they never asked for anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West said he typically recommends early release for prisoners  
who do not break jail rules, especially those who are successful on 
work-release programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Amish prisoners mixed well with the other inmates, except on  
the jail's basketball court. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Amish were good, really good, and some of the other guys  
wouldn't play with them,'' West said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
