<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Certifies 15 Div. I Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The NCAA on Thursday classified 15 Division  
I schools as fully certified and two others, Jacksonville State and 
Sam Houston State, as certified with conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Certification, required for all Division I members, was mandated  
at the association's convention in 1993. Since then, 273 of the 310 
schools in the largest NCAA division have received certification 
that they operate their athletic programs in conformity with NCAA 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	A conditional certification means the school is in substantial  
conformity but has had problems that must be corrected before full 
certification is granted. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA Committee on Athletics Certification said Jacksonville  
State must submit by June 1, 2000, a plan on gender equity and 
minority opportunities in its sports programs. By March 1, 2000, 
Sam Houston State must account for all money raised and spent by 
the university's Lettermen's Association. 
</P>
<P>
	If a school fails to meet the deadline for correcting a problem,  
the NCAA may place it in a restricted membership category for one 
year. If the problem still exists after one year, the school may be 
stripped of active membership in the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools have 15 days to request a hearing before the  
certification committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 15 given full certification on Thursday is Virginia  
Tech, whose status was upgraded from certified with conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The others are Arkansas-Little Rock, California-Irvine,  
Connecticut, Indiana-Purdue-Indianapolis, Indiana State, 
Mississippi, Norfolk State, Northern Arizona, Penn State, Purdue, 
Robert Morris, Toledo, Virginia Commonwealth and Wofford. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
