<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Denies Brown Threatened Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Domestic violence charges against Hall of  
Fame football star Jim Brown are based on lies his wife made out of 
frustration because she believed he was having an affair, his 
defense attorney said in opening statements Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``She wanted to get a reaction from Jim. She wanted to do  
something dramatic,'' said William Graysen. ``Monique's whole story 
was made up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Brown on June 15 after his wife, Monique Brown,  
called 911 following an argument with her husband at their Beverly 
Hills home. She later denied she was ever in danger or threatened 
by her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	The city attorney's domestic violence unit decided to go ahead  
and prosecute Brown. City attorney's officials said that two-thirds 
of domestic violence victims seen by the unit recant their stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors charge that Brown threatened to kill his wife during  
the argument and that he shattered windows of her car with a 
shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who pleaded innocent, has alleged that police forced his  
wife to say she was abused. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 63, is on trial for one count of making terrorist threats  
and one count of vandalism, both misdemeanors. Four women and eight 
men were picked Friday to serve as jurors in the trial set to 
resume Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Grace Lee countered Graysen's remarks with the  
contention that Monique Brown was abused previously by the 
defendant, but the June 15 argument was the first time she called 
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown, 25, was choked on one occasion and in another  
sustained a black eye, Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of you recognize him as an athlete ... but this case is  
about the private individual Jim Brown and the acts of violence he 
committed,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown told reporters as he entered the court Friday that he was  
being targeted because of who he is. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say they don't give celebrities special privileges. But  
we would not be here over a month if it was anyone else,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown sat in the front row of the courtroom during  
opening arguments Friday while her husband sat with his attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown has said previously she called 911 because she was  
angry and ``was trying to get leverage.'' There was no emergency, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	As she entered the court with her husband Friday she told  
reporters she ``made one mistake'' and ``didn't create all this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Brown could be sentenced to 18 months in jail,  
three years' probation and ordered to complete domestic violence 
counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown retired from pro football in 1966. He set many National  
Football League rushing and scoring records as a running back for 
the Cleveland Browns. He has also appeared in Hollywood movies, 
including ``The Dirty Dozen'' and ``Mars Attacks!'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
