<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 16:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Chmura Not Ready To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers tight end Mark Chmura  
says he's not ready to retire as a result of a neck injury that 
temporarily caused him to lose feeling in his upper body. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, if the doctors said I should retire, then I would.  
But everything I hear is great, so I'm continuing,'' Chmura told 
The Post-Crescent of Appleton in Friday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Chmura has a bulging cervical disc in his neck. The tight end's  
agent, Eric Metz, said he and Chmura's wife, Lynda, have suggested 
to the 30-year-old three-time Pro Bowl selection that he retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Metz has represented former Detroit Lions offensive lineman Mike  
Utley, who was paralyzed in a 1991 game and uses a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm encouraging Mark to retire,'' Metz said. ``But I don't  
think he will. ... Mark is more tough than he is prudent when it 
comes to football. He's a player. He wants to play, but I wish he'd 
leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys love to play,'' Metz added. ``I guarantee you, if  
Mike Utley could get out of his wheelchair, the first thing he'd do 
is run to the football field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chmura, an eight-year NFL veteran, lost feeling in his upper  
body Aug. 5 when he was hit by defensive end Vaughn Booker. He 
continued to practice until his back locked up Aug. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking three days off, Chmura experienced the same loss of  
sensation the morning of Aug. 12, when he was on his knees striking 
a blocking sled. Chmura continues to recover and he is not ruling 
himself out of playing in the final exhibition game against Miami 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark has gotten great care and we do trust the Packers,'' Metz  
said. ``But it still makes me nervous. I just don't think he should 
be running around in a helmet crashing into 300-pound guys right 
now with a bad neck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chmura said he won't start contact until he is sure he is  
healthy. He admitted that retirement was his first thought when he 
was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Ray Rhodes and general manager Ron Wolf have said Chmura  
won't be pushed to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark will be back when he's ready,'' Rhodes said this week.  
``His health is the most important thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Metz said he doesn't want Chmura to play until he is completely  
ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may still have to retire,'' Metz said. ``He's not out of  
the woods yet.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
