<DOCNO> APW19990827.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 11:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cadillac Unveils Redesigned Logo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- For the first time in 36 years, Cadillac is  
modifying its familiar wreath-and-crest logo in another step to 
shake its stodgy image. 
</P>
<P>
	While the changes to the historic emblem are small, Cadillac's  
leader says they show how committed the automaker is to luring 
younger buyers into its showrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new wreath and crest depicts a forward-looking and  
youthful image while maintaining distinctiveness and a sense of 
prestige,'' John F. Smith, Cadillac general manager, said in a 
statement Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The logo's changes include eliminating the six birds, called  
merlettes, in the crest, as well as the crown, or coronet, on top. 
The wreath surrounding the crest also is being streamlined. 
</P>
<P>
	The result is a design that evokes paintings by Piet Mondrian,  
the Dutch abstract painter who used blocks of primary colors. It's 
also meant to evoke the ``art and science'' styling theme from the 
edgy Evoq roadster concept car on display at this year's major auto 
shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The logo won't appear on passenger cars from the luxury division  
of General Motors Corp. until 2001. But it has already shown up on 
one Cadillac -- the company's entry in this year's Le Mans 24 Hours 
race, its first in half a century. 
</P>
<P>
	The new logo will also be used in some advertising later this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadillac's recent efforts to woo young drivers has been less  
than successful. Sales of the imported Catera entry-level sedan 
have been a disappointment, while demand for the larger Seville, 
redesigned for the '98 model year, was down 23 percent in the first 
half of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year ended with the ultimate humiliation: Cadillac lost the  
U.S. luxury sales crown it had held for 48 years to rival Ford 
Motor Co.'s Lincoln division -- largely because of Lincoln's popular 
sport utility vehicle, the Navigator. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first half of this year, Cadillac's U.S. car sales  
declined 15 percent while overall luxury car sales increased 7 
percent. Including SUV sales, Cadillac now trails Lexus, 
Mercedes-Benz and BMW -- all of which are benefiting from fresher, 
more innovative models. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadillac hopes to change that starting with the redesigned  
Escalade, which will debut in 2001 for Cadillac's centennial model 
year of 2002. That will be followed by several new models, 
including an all-new, car-based SUV and the limited-production 
Evoq. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Search for Water in Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Having found water in a 4.5 billion-year-old  
meteorite, NASA scientists are searching for more that may have 
been overlooked in other space rocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The water, locked in a purple crystalline mineral called halite  
-- or rock salt -- remained uncontaminated by the Earth's atmosphere 
because scientists studied the meteorite quickly, less than 46 
hours after it fell, said Everett Gibson, the NASA scientist who 
retrieved the space rock last year from the West Texas town of 
Monahans. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson said, ``If one can be recovered quickly, please take care  
of it.'' He advised anyone who finds a new meteorite to wrap it up 
and keep it from moisture. 
</P>
<P>
	While some look to the heavens for further signs of  
extraterrestrial water, other examples may be sitting in display 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going around to museums to look for falls from the past  
that were immediately curated in dry laboratories,'' said Michael 
Zolensky of NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Zolensky, who described the discovery Friday in the journal  
Science, said that older meteorites may still contain water trapped 
deep inside. He has already found a Moroccan asteroid called Zag 
that shows signs of containing water. 
</P>
<P>
	The Monahans meteorite dates back to the birth of the solar  
system, when the sun and planets were a condensing spiral of dust 
and gas. The tiny bubbles found inside provide the first close look 
at water not originating on Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've known for some time that there was water in the early  
solar system because we've seen evidence for it,'' Zolensky said. 
</P>
<P>
	The presence of salt is even more mysterious than the water,  
since sodium chloride usually forms when large bodies of water like 
oceans evaporate, Zolensky said. 
</P>
<P>
	The meteorite may be a piece of a larger asteroid that had  
liquid water flowing over its surface. An icy comet could have 
slammed into the asteroid, delivering the water which then boiled 
off very quickly, leaving behind the salt crystals with water 
trapped inside. Another theory is that ice inside an asteroid may 
have been heated by radioactive decay, creating the halite. 
</P>
<P>
	While life beyond Earth remains elusive, the presence of water  
improves the odds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we know from this meteorite that there must have been a  
lot of water around for quite a while and the same meteorites have 
organics. That basically says all the conditions were there for 
getting some biology going,'' Zolensky said. 
</P>
<P>
	While halite is normally clear, the purple crystals found in the  
meteorite likely changed color after being exposed to radiation in 
space. This helps confirm the uncontaminated origin of the water, 
said Robert Bodnar, a professor of geochemistry at Virginia Tech, 
who first confirmed water in the meteorite. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of water is too small to be analyzed in complete  
detail, but new equipment being developed should reveal its origins 
-- whether from the solar system or from interstellar space, Bodnar 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	First seen as a bright green streak in the sky above Monahans,  
the 2.2-pound meteorite struck about 40 feet from where seven boys 
were playing basketball on March 22, 1998. Worried that it might be 
radioactive, the boys and their families over turned the rock to 
the fire department. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA scientists arrived soon after and borrowed the rock for a  
few days to study it and take samples. After it was returned to the 
town, the boys challenged the city council's claims that the rock 
fell on public property and belonged to the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually the city relented and gave the meteorite to the boys,  
who then sold it to Mike Craddock for $23,000 during an Internet 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Craddock said he wanted ``a piece of West Texas history,'' but  
the new discovery has made his potato-sized rock even more 
important. 
</P>
<P>
	He said when he bought it he ``thought this must be the most  
famous meteorite in the United States. Now that it's the first 
meteorite with water in it, it may be the most famous meteorite in 
the world.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 19:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ducks Sign Defenseman Pavel Trnka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The Anaheim Mighty Ducks agreed to terms  
with defenseman Pavel Trnka on a three-year contract on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trnka appeared in 63 games last season, with four assists and 60  
penalty minutes. The 6-foot-3, 205-pounder has played in 111 NHL 
games, with three goals and eight assists and 100 penalty minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Trnka, 23, was Anaheim's fifth-round selection (106th overall)  
in the 1994 NHL entry draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional contract details weren't available.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
