<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Backs Some Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- Less than 10 miles from where a distraught  
day trader killed himself after his bloody shooting spree left nine 
dead, Texas Gov. George W. Bush called gun-control measures 
currently being considered by Congress ``reasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate said Friday he agrees with  
banning certain large ammunition clips and raising the legal age 
for gun ownership from 18 to 21. Bush also repeated his support for 
instant background checks on firearms sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are all reasonable measures,'' the GOP front-runner told  
reporters after touring a homeless shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments came after several violent episodes in metropolitan  
Atlanta over the past three months, culminating in Mark O. Barton's 
shooting spree in two Atlanta office buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, a sophomore wounded six classmates in a suburban Conyers  
high school, and just two weeks before Barton's rampage a man 
killed two women and four children in their Atlanta home before 
killing himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has been criticized by Democrats as being soft on gun  
control. He has previously spoken against government-mandated gun 
registration, signed legislation barring cities in Texas from suing 
gun makers, and deemed mandatory child safety locks on firearms 
impractical to enforce. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Bush stressed that he still believes in gun rights.  
``I believe innocent people, law-abiding citizens, ought to be 
allowed to own a gun. I believe they ought to be allowed to hunt 
and protect themselves,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added that current gun restrictions should be enforced  
more stringently. 
</P>
<P>
	``There ought to be consequences, and those consequences ought  
to be called jail,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Bush picked up approximately $250,000 in campaign  
contributions from a $1,000-a-plate luncheon in nearby Smyrna. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Futures Dip  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Natural gas futures sank Friday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after storms that had threatened offshore production areas 
moved on or petered out. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil prices rebounded for a second straight day after  
taking a big hit earlier in the week. On other markets, soybean and 
cocoa futures gained. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas saw its first big price dip since June after the  
last immediate storm threat, Hurricane Dennis, was reported to be 
headed for the East Coast and not the Gulf of Mexico as feared. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other storms also were deemed to pose little threat.  
</P>
<P>
	``The weather threat is gone,'' said Bill O'Grady, an energy  
analyst for AG Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis, explaining 
Friday's price falloff. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindy, upgraded to a hurricane again late Wednesday, was far out  
in the Atlantic. And Emily -- which sprang up at near-hurricane 
strength Tuesday -- began to lose strength and was downgraded to a 
tropical depression. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for September delivery fell 36 cents to $2.87 per  
1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude advanced past the $21-a-barrel level again after falling  
to $20.58 on Wednesday on an industry report that gasoline 
inventories had fallen. 
</P>
<P>
	October crude fell 32 cents to $21.27 a barrel; September  
heating oil rose .05 cent to 55.99 cents a gallon; September 
unleaded gasoline gained 1.88 cents to 66.11 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude for delivery in October rose 19  
cents to $20.76 a barrel at the International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures pushed higher on the Chicago Board of Trade,  
partly on the strength of forecasts for dry weather for most of the 
soybean belt next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were buoyed by continued market talk that China is  
in the market for U.S. soybean products and may have bought between 
250,000 tons and 350,000 tons of soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	November soybeans rose 4 1/4 cents to $4.71 a bushel. Grain prices  
were mostly down -- wheat for December delivery fell 4 cents to 
$2.79 1/2 a bushel; December corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.15 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats were unchanged at $1.14 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures rose amid fears that Ivory Coast's moves toward  
free-market policies will result in trouble for growers in 
negotiations with traders. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa officials say that after similar moves Ghana and Cameroon  
have experienced problems with agents pressuring them to harvest 
too early, causing quality to suffer. 
</P>
<P>
	September cocoa rose $23 to $895 a ton on the Coffee, Sugar &AMP;  
Cocoa Exchange division of the New York Board of Trade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 07:53:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  500,000 Turks Could Be Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Turkish officials acknowledged for the  
first time today that the number of those left homeless by last 
week's earthquake could top half a million. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is now projecting it will need to build about  
100,000 to 120,000 new homes for quake victims, said Harun Aslan, 
spokesman for the Ministry of Housing and Public Works. With about 
five people per household, that works out to between 500,000 and 
600,000 displaced people, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added those figures were still preliminary. Up until now,  
the government has said only that quake homeless numbered in the 
tens of thousands, ranging up to 200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	New signs also emerged today that the quake has exacerbated  
friction between Turkey's secular government and religious groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The government, highly sensitive about the activities of Islamic  
groups, especially radical organizations that want to topple it, 
froze the bank accounts of two Islamic groups that have been active 
in quake-relief efforts. The two groups -- the Muslim-oriented 
Mazlum Der and another called Human Rights and Freedoms -- 
complained they were being targeted because of their faith. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction and safety issues remained in the spotlight today.  
The Daily News, a nationally circulated Turkish newspaper, reported 
that three-quarters of Istanbul's buildings, most of them in 
shantytowns ringing the city, are unlicensed and illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	The monstrous Aug. 17 quake, which killed at least 13,472 people  
and injured 27,164, has focused the public's attention on the 
dangers of shoddy construction. Substandard building has been 
blamed for the collapse of thousands of structures across the quake 
zone and on the outskirts of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, Ross Mountain, the head of the U.N. humanitarian  
affairs department, said foreign search and rescue teams had been 
``appalled'' by the poor quality of cement and lack of 
reinforcement in collapsed buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Thursday whether unsafe buildings should be torn down  
preemptively, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit seemed wary, saying: 
``It's not that easy to destroy all existing (unsafe) buildings in 
Istanbul entirely.'' However, he said, it is important to prosecute 
those who had previously built unsafe structures, and to improve 
inspections for buildings under construction now. 
</P>
<P>
	Worry that quake-damaged buildings could cause new deaths and  
injury boiled over into violence in at least one case, the Anatolia 
news agency said. It reported Thursday that a shootout left two 
people dead after two families got into a bitter argument because 
the quake-wrecked home of one was leaning onto the home of the 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	In the quake zone, a team of at least 400 architects and  
engineers was dispatched to help local authorities decide which 
quake-damaged buildings should be torn down first. In the town of 
Golcuk today, crews marked buildings slated for demolition with a 
large red X. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have urged those whose houses were declared safe to  
return home. But with aftershocks and new quakes continuing to 
rattle the region, the tens of thousands of quake-damaged buildings 
still looming over the city were prompting safety fears. 
</P>
<P>
	Small quakes kept rocking Turkey. A 3.7-magnitude temblor hit  
the ravaged town of Adapazari at 8:35 p.m. Thursday, followed 14 
minutes later by another with a 4.1 magnitude, the Anatolia news 
agency said. There were no reported injuries or damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, a 3.7-magnitude quake shook the central city of Corum  
without causing any reported damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The death toll from the huge quake was expected to climb.  
Thousands of people are believed still buried under the rubble, and 
few if any survivors are expected to be found after this long. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the government announced Thursday that rescue crews  
were still looking for more survivors. It said 621 people had been 
saved from the ruins since the quake. 
</P>
<P>
	On Istanbul's volatile stock market, worried investors sent the  
index down by some 10 percent on Thursday -- the first day of 
trading since the quake. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to raise part of the estimated $20 billion needed to  
repair the damage, the government has proposed raising taxes by 5 
percent on corporations, the self-employed and wealthy wage earners 
and adding a 25 percent monthly surcharge on cellular telephones as 
well as additional taxes on motor vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are widely expected to be approved by the full  
assembly, where the coalition government has a strong majority. But 
they have already stirred controversy among those wondering whether 
the new tax money would actually be spent in the quake zone. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
