<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 01:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks End Down / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen in  
mid-afternoon trading Friday, while Japanese stocks closed lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 111.58 yen in the late morning, up 0.52 yen  
from its level of 111.06 yen late Thursday in Tokyo and also above 
its late New York level of 111.54 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down 66.92  
points, or 0.38 percent, at 17,599.37 points. On Thursday, the 
average closed down 188.87 points, or 1.06 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was supported by talk in the  
market that deputy finance ministers from the Group of Seven 
nations are set to meet this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are reluctant to sell the dollar aggressively ahead of  
the weekend with vague talk (of) a G-7 deputies meeting,'' said 
Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN AMRO 
Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Upcoming events helped bolster such speculation: Haruhiko  
Kuroda, Japanese vice finance minister for international affairs, 
is planning to attend a meeting of Asian and U.S. finance deputies 
on Sunday and Monday in Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the yen's outlook against the dollar remains  
uncertain amid a tug-of-war between continued demand for the 
Japanese currency among global investors to invest in markets here 
and fears of central bank intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has entered the market to buy dollars in  
recent months to stem the yen's rapid rise against the U.S. 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, cutting into earnings of export-oriented 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 116.96 yen in  
mid-afternoon trading, up from 115.72 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei average closed lower amid  
concern that domestic investors could start selling ahead of the 
end of the first half of the fiscal year on Sept. 30, said Chuck 
Lambert, market analyst at Jardine Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the small rebound in the dollar against the yen kept the  
stock market higher much of Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also got a lift from news Friday morning that  
spending by Japanese wage earners in July was up 2.6 percent in 
real terms from a year earlier. Economists surveyed had estimated 
on average that spending would rise 0.4 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average fell  
127.59 points to 11,198.45 at Thursday's close after setting a new 
record high Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 2.70 points, or 0.18 percent, to 1,478.38. 
The TOPIX closed down 13.72 points, or 0.09 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.9350 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.9400 
percent, driving its price up to 99.70 yen from 99.66 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
