<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Modifies Purchase Circles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Concern over consumer privacy has prompted  
Internet retailer Amazon.com to make changes in its new service 
designed to help gift buyers find its most popular products among 
certain demographics. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Thursday it was modifying its new Purchase  
Circles feature to allow employers to opt out of the 
company-specific listings and let customers have their purchases 
excluded from the anonymous listings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Privacy is of utmost importance to our customers and to us,''  
said Warren Adams, director of product development. ``While the 
vast majority of feedback from our customers indicates that 
Purchase Circles have been well received and are extremely valuable 
..., some customers have expressed concerns, so we're letting 
people decide individually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said the changes will be implemented ``as soon as  
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The service is designed to help purchasers find the 10 hottest  
products in 3,000 different cities, universities and workplaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Purchase Circles debuted on Amazon.com's Web site last Friday.  
The Seattle-based company uses technology to collect consumer data, 
which it makes available in searchable databases, where online 
shoppers could see which books or music CDs are most popular with 
people in a certain area code, employer or military branch. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com had already found great success with a service that  
suggests merchandise to suit shoppers' own interests. Under the 
Purchase Circle plan, a customer also is able to track everything 
from the most popular CDs ordered in Miami to best-selling books at 
Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	To create a Purchase Circle, Amazon.com collects buying  
information based on what products it ships to a particular Zip 
code. It also tracks goods bought by people with the same e-mail 
address. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
