<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton golfed with Prince  
Andrew today and jokingly bet the island of Martha's Vineyard on 
the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and the Duke of York teed off at Farm Neck Golf Club  
where the president, with the prince as a passenger, stopped his 
golf cart in front of a gaggle of reporters and photographers and 
introduced his royal guest. 
</P>
<P>
	The dukes of York, he asserted, were hereditary owners of  
Martha's Vineyard, located in the Atlantic off the Massachusetts 
coast, in the 17th century. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what the bet is? If he beats me we have to give him  
back the island,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you want the island back, sir,'' a reporter shouted.  
</P>
<P>
	Andrew smiled.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you when I've won,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The prince was heard to say that the play would be without a  
handicap, ``flat, no strokes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the foursome were Sir Evelyn Rothschild of London  
and a man preliminarily identified by the White House as Tony 
Fisher of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The golf outing came after Clinton ended two days of seclusion  
at his borrowed summer house with a burst of vacation activity on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He went horseback riding. Then he played golf, twice, 34 holes  
in all. Then he threw on a sweater and, accompanied by first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton and their daughter Chelsea, joined friends 
at a clambake on the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The clambake at the home of Mattel executive Bill Rollnick and  
his wife, Nancy Ellison, is an annual event. The Clintons were 
there two years ago when an aide told them Princess Diana had been 
killed in an automobile crash in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The clambake provided a quiet conclusion to what otherwise was a  
busy day for Clinton. In a stark turnaround from the seclusion he'd 
been in for the two previous days, the president arose early and 
headed to the Blue Heron Farm for a morning of horseback riding. 
</P>
<P>
	A squadron of wild geese flew over a nearby field as Clinton and  
Chelsea rode on sandy narrow paths through groves of oak trees at 
the 40-acre farm. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton left after an hour and spent the rest of the day at the  
Farm Neck Golf Club playing golf with two sets of college friends. 
During the first round with Warren Spector, Tom Flexner and Ken 
Iscol -- all of New York City -- Clinton sent his first shot into the 
woods, a well-traveled territory for Clinton golf balls. 
</P>
<P>
	During a later round with Clare O'Callahan, Maurie Flanagan and  
her son, Sean, Clinton paused after his first shot and asked: ``Is 
it OK?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Hit one more. Go ahead,'' replied Sean. So Clinton did.  
</P>
<P>
	``Much better,'' O'Callahan offered.  
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons are scheduled to leave Martha's Vineyard off the  
Massachusetts coast on Saturday for a round of fund-raisers in the 
posh Hamptons district of eastern Long Island. Beneficiaries will 
include the Democratic National Committee and Mrs. Clinton's 
expected campaign to win an open U.S. Senate seat in New York 
state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Computers Vulnerable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Department computer systems  
controlling critical operations from weapons design to soldiers' 
payrolls remain vulnerable to hackers, government auditors said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office said ``weaknesses in DOD  
information security continue to provide both hackers and hundreds 
of thousands of authorized users the opportunity to modify, steal, 
inappropriately disclose and destroy sensitive DOD data.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some corrective efforts have been undertaken in response  
to earlier recommendations, the GAO said progress has been 
``inconsistent across the various DOD components,'' including 
controls over who can physically or electronically access sensitive 
computer systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Users were granted access to computer resources that exceeded  
what they required to carry out their job responsibilities,'' the 
congressional watchdog agency said in a report. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokeswoman Susan Hansen said the GAO report was  
welcomed as a way of helping to raise awareness of the problem and 
that it was ``right in line with the types of things that we are 
ready to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department, perhaps the largest user of such  
information systems in the world, spends roughly $1 billion a year 
on computer system security, and has requested more money from 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``To put the kinds of corrections in will require consistent  
efforts, and those cost,'' Hansen said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Defense Secretary William Cohen's office and other  
operations within the Pentagon had recently set up additional 
firewalls and password protection for information systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Hansen also said a department-wide effort aimed at consolidating  
such computer security efforts throughout the military is on 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO report noted that it was too early to assess the success  
of this program. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 14:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan's Assets Down in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan knows  
more about what makes the economy tick than most people, but he 
apparently lost some money last year. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Greenspan's most recent financial disclosure form,  
the value of his assets in 1998 ranged from around $2.5 million to 
$6.4 million, less than the range of around $3.4 million to $7.3 
million he reported for 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures are not precise because the value of each asset is  
reported using a wide range, not a specific amount. 
</P>
<P>
	So where does Greenspan -- who once warned of ``irrational  
exuberance'' in financial markets -- put his own money? He shuns the 
stock market for the safest investment of all -- short-term Treasury 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan -- who made $136,700 last year in his government job --  
didn't have any stock holdings, reflecting his desire to avoid any 
conflict of interest, Fed officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The words and actions of Greenspan and his Fed colleagues, who  
set interest rate policies, can send stocks soaring or make them 
plummet. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his holdings, Greenspan listed one Treasury bill valued at  
more than $1 million and three Treasury bills worth between 
$500,001 to 1 million, according to the financial disclosure 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The form also showed that Greenspan sold a Norfolk Southern bond  
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan has filed financial disclosure forms every year since  
he was sworn in as Federal Reserve chairman in August 1987. But 
until last year, they said simply that most of his assets were in a 
blind trust worth more than $1 million. He liquidated the trust 
after his 1997 marriage to NBC-TV correspondent Andrea Mitchell so 
the couple could make joint financial plans, Fed officials have 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Greenspan's holdings, his wife's portfolio is weighted  
heavily toward stocks, including holdings in Abbott Laboratories, 
H.J. Heinz Co., American Greetings Corp. and Anheuser Busch Cos. 
Inc. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
