<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SNET Criticized Over E-Mail Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- SNET Internet is being criticized for  
the way it has handled a two-week-old problem that is still causing 
long delays in the delivery of e-mails to its customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The delays are affecting incoming messages being sent to 130,000  
SNET customers statewide, but are not affecting SNET e-mail 
messages sent to other systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Wirth, a business customer, said Thursday that the snafu  
has hurt his business. He said Southern New England 
Telecommunications Corp. has bungled its communications to 
customers about the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisory messages posted on SNET's Web page are inadequate, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wirth, managing director of the Institute for Business  
Technology in Stratford, said SNET should have been more candid 
about the problem so he and other affected customers could have 
made other arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like hanging by your thumbs every day,'' Wirth told the  
Connecticut Post. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the company Thursday received 15 messages that were five  
days late. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's worse than the United States Postal Service,'' Wirth  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even non-SNET customers are being affected. John Watson, a  
Westport stockbroker, is not a SNET customer, but has sent e-mails 
to SNET customers. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he received them back two days later, but had no way of  
knowing why they were ``undeliverable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not working I'd like to know,'' Watson said.  
</P>
<P>
	SNET said it has been updating customers via its website.  
Customers who call the company's customer service line hear a 
recording stating that there is a problem with the service. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial problem -- a hard drive that overheated on Aug. 10 --  
has been fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the delay it caused in the receipt of e-mail has  
created a backlog that multiplies every time messages don't get 
through and systems or people resend them. 
</P>
<P>
	SNET spokeswoman Beverly Levy said the company cannot offer any  
timetable to customers for when the service will be back to normal. 
</P>
<P>
	SNET customers with the company's long distance service pay  
$18.99 a month for unlimited Internet access. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
