<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Southeast Readies for Hurricane  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- People began preparing for Hurricane  
Dennis from the Bahamas to the Carolinas today, banging wood over 
windows, battening down roofs and stocking up on supplies. By early 
evening, Dennis was 315 miles southeast of Cape Canaveral on 
Florida's east coast. It could near the Carolinas within days. In 
South Carolina, Gov. Jim Hodges ordered 1,000 National Guard troops 
and 500 state troopers to prepare for duty, but no decision was 
made yet on any possible coastal evacuation. In North Carolina, 
emergency planners urged 150,000 coastal residents to get ready for 
the storm. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Optimistic on Mideast Accord  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said  
today she was hopeful Israel and the Palestinians will conclude a 
long-sought agreement that would turn over more of the West Bank to 
Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority. Albright was upbeat after a 
firsthand report from Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and 
Arafat's deputy, Mahmoud Abbas, widely known as Abu Mazen. ``I 
think we are looking forward to the conclusion of this aspect of 
the peace process,'' she said. 

</P>
<P>
	30 Hurt in Venezuela Clashes  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Police fired water cannons and tear  
gas today to break up clashes between supporters and opponents of 
Venezuela's president outside the country's parliamentary building. 
During the fight, supporters of President Hugo Chavez and the 
National Guard tried to prevent opposition lawmakers from entering 
the Capitol building. Chavez's critics countered with shouts of 
``No to dictatorship!'' The defiant lawmakers broke through the 
crowd and climbed over the fence. Authorities said at least 30 
people were injured in the clashes. 

</P>
<P>
	Beleaguered Mir Crew Undocks  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The last full-time crew undocked from the Mir  
early Saturday, bidding farewell to the 13-year-old Russian space 
station in preparation for its abandonment next year. Next spring, 
the Mir is scheduled to leave outer space and burn up in the 
atmosphere. The crew's departure was a low point for the Russian 
space program, which put the first satellite in the cosmos, as well 
as the first man and first woman -- and now has no cash, no new 
projects entirely its own and a dim view of the future. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbia/HCA Removing 900 Doctors  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Columbia/HCA Healthcare Inc., the  
nation's largest hospital chain, has removed about 900 doctors from 
its payroll as part of a restructuring brought on by a federal 
fraud investigation into the company. Columbia once owned physician 
practices that employed 1,500 doctors. Like most hospitals, 
Columbia lost money owning physician practices. Hospitals largely 
found when they put doctors on salary, the physicians tended to 
work less and did little to boost their practices' revenues. 

</P>
<P>
	Vets Prepare Elephant Anesthetic  
</P>
<P>
	LAMPANG, Thailand (AP) -- Soldiers in northern Thailand today  
sterilized the open-air operating theater where veterinarians will 
attempt to save the land mine-shattered left leg of Motola the 
elephant. Veterinarians prepared enough anesthetic to knock out 70 
humans, readied some 130 gallons of glucose and lactose and 
gathered dozens of mammoth-sized dressings to stem the bleeding 
from Saturday's surgery. Motola, the three ton cow elephant, trod 
on a land mine nearly two weeks ago as she foraged for food at a 
logging camp along the Myanmar-Thai border, the scene of a 
half-century of insurgencies. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan: Market Has Larger Role  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve needs to pay closer  
attention to what happens on Wall Street, Chairman Alan Greenspan 
said today, since Americans reaping the rewards of the high-flying 
stock market are using those paper profits to justify spending and 
other financial decisions. Some economists interpreted Greenspan's 
comments as a signal that the Fed may further raise interest rates 
this year. Two previous increases -- this week and on June 30 -- have 
not dampened the Wall Street stock-buying ``exuberance.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 108.28  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today amid fear that the Fed isn't  
finished raising interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average 
was down 108.28 to 11,090.17. Declining issues on the NYSE led 
advancers 1,777-1,133. The Nasdaq was down 15.73 at 2,758.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Grizzlies Swing 3-Way Deal  
</P>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- In a three way deal involving  
the Houston Rockets and the Orlando Magic, the Vancouver Grizzlies 
sent Steve Francis to the Rockets. Along with Francis, Houston got 
journeyman forward Tony Massenberg from the Grizzlies. In return, 
the Grizzlies got forwards Othella Harrington and Antoine Carr and 
guards Michael Dickerson and Brent Price from Houston, as well as a 
future first-round draft pick. From Orlando, the Grizzlies got the 
Magic's second-round draft pick in 2002. As part of the deal, the 
Magic sent Don MacLean to Houston, in exchange for Grizzlies 
Michael Smith, Lee Mayberry, Rodrick Rhodes and Makhtar Ndiaye. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
