<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Troopers on Alert As Hurricane Nears  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis, which kicked up high  
surf hundreds of miles away off North Carolina's Outer Banks today, 
could strike the east coast of Florida soon, forecasters warned. 
The governor of North Carolina put state troopers on alert and 
National Guard troops prepared for storm duty in South Carolina as 
a hurricane watch was posted for Florida's eastern coast. 

</P>
<P>
	Mir Crew Returns to Earth  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The last full-time crew undocked from the Mir and  
returned to Earth early Saturday, bidding farewell to the 
rust-stained, rattling, 13-year-old Russian space station that will 
be abandoned next year. Crew commander Viktor Afanasyev, cosmonaut 
Sergei Avdeyev and French astronaut Jean-Paul Haignere landed 
safely in a deserted steppe in the former Soviet republic 
Kazakstan. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Banks Bleed the Economy  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- In Russia's murky financial world, one thing is  
certain: billions of dollars pour out of the country every year 
illegally, much of it looted by the Russian mob and big businesses, 
and almost no one is ever caught. In the latest in a series of 
scandals, investigators believe that the Russian mob may have 
laundered billions of dollars in accounts at the Bank of New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan: Market Bears Watching  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve needs to pay closer  
attention to what happens on Wall Street, Chairman Alan Greenspan 
said today, since Americans reaping the rewards of the high-flying 
stock market are using those paper profits to justify spending and 
other financial decisions. Some economists interpreted Greenspan's 
comments as a signal that the Fed may further raise interest rates 
this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Blamed for Afghan Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Pakistan came under unusually blunt  
criticism in the Security Council today, accused of supporting 
Afghanistan's Taliban militia and helping fuel its recent offensive 
with weapons and warriors. Pakistan's ambassador, Inam ul Haque, 
denied his government supported any side in Afghanistan, but 
allowed that some Pakistanis on their own may have crossed the 
border to fight. 

</P>
<P>
	30 Hurt in Venezuela Clashes  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Police fired water cannons and tear  
gas today to break up clashes between supporters and opponents of 
Venezuela's president outside the country's parliamentary building. 
During the fight, supporters of President Hugo Chavez and the 
National Guard tried to prevent opposition lawmakers from entering 
the Capitol building. Chavez's critics countered with shouts of 
``No to dictatorship!'' The lawmakers climbed over the fence. 
Authorities said at least 30 people were injured in the clashes. 

</P>
