<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phelps Dodge Bids for Asarco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phelps Dodge Corp. launched a $2.5 billion  
hostile bid Friday to acquire Asarco Inc. and Cyprus Amax Minerals 
Co., soliciting shareholders directly after being rebuffed by the 
companies' boards. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we continue to prefer negotiated transactions, we are  
committed to this compelling three-way combination and are taking 
all necessary steps to complete it,'' said Douglas C. Yearley, 
chairman and chief executive of the Phoenix-based Phelps Dodge. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Asarco and Englewood, Colo.-based Cyprus Amax,  
two of the world's leading copper and metals producers, have 
already agreed to merge to form the nation's largest copper 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	In a filing Friday with the Securities and Exchange Commission,  
Phelps Dodge said it was undertaking the hostile bid and rejecting 
the two companies' counteroffer, made Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Amax and Asarco had indicated they were interested in  
discussing a deal, but wanted $650 million more in stock than what 
Phelps Dodge was offering. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge's offer Friday remained unchanged from its offer  
last week, except that shareholders would receive cash for any 
fractional Phelps Dodge shares if they accept the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Vahid Fathi, a mining and metals analyst at ABN Amro Inc. in  
Chicago, wasn't surprised by Phelps Dodge's refusal of the 
counteroffer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paying up the asking price Cyprus and Asarco are currently  
insisting on would completely take all the economic benefits of the 
deal away from Phelps Dodge shareholders,'' said Fathi. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge is asking Asarco and Cyprus Amax stockholders to  
vote against the proposed merger of Asarco and Cyprus, but said it 
would not bid further if shareholders of those two companies 
approved the combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phelps Dodge is making a very smart move ... that they would  
walk away if the merger goes through,'' Fathi said. ``That behooves 
shareholders of Asarco and Cyprus Amax to think twice before voting 
for this merger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an enticement to shareholders, the two companies have said  
they will pay them an extra $5 per share if the merger is approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Amax declined comment. Asarco could not immediately be  
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate action, Phelps Dodge also sued the two companies  
and their directors, alleging they breached their financial duties 
by not allowing directors to learn more about a possible 
third-party purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge recently slashed its production by closing mines,  
smelters and refineries throughout the Southwest, laying off about 
1,650 workers in Arizona, New Mexico and Texas. The industry has 
suffered in the wake of falling copper prices and lower copper 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of all three companies fell slightly Friday during  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Phelps Dodge dropped 6 1/4 
cents to $56.62 1/2, Cyprus Amax fell 25 cents to $17.56 1/4 and Asarco 
fell 6 1/4 cents to $22.68 3/4. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 00:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Rising for Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Monica Lewis fumed as she filled the tank  
of her Saab 900S at a Mobil station in downtown Stamford. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is ridiculous,'' she snapped, looking up at pump prices  
ranging from $1.39 to $1.63 per gallon. ``I used to buy the 
mid-grade. Now, I've got to go with the cheapest. I have to buy 
food, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Motorists across New England are exasperated by a sharp rise in  
gas prices over the last month. Nationally, the average increase in 
self-service unleaded this month was the biggest since 1990, 
following Iraq's attack on Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I don't even look anymore they're so bad,'' said  
Tony Zeppieri, who filled his tank Thursday at a Mobil station in 
Richmond, R.I., where the price for unleaded was $1.27 per gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut has the highest prices in the region -- an average  
$1.37 per gallon for regular unleaded self-serve -- after a 9-cent 
increase during the last month, according to the most recent survey 
by the American Automobile Association. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rhode Island, the average price is $1.28 per gallon, followed  
by Massachusetts, Maine, Vermont and New Hampshire, at $1.22. 
Connecticut was already stinging from a 12-cent jump in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The association said the national average price of unleaded has  
risen 8.1 cents per gallon in the past month. The increase -- to 
$1.255 a gallon -- is the biggest from one month to another since 
prices soared 11.4 cents after Iraq attacked Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the pre-Labor Day average price was $1.08 a gallon.  
</P>
<P>
	With Labor Day coming up, motorists said they are particularly  
concerned about the gas prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it continues to increase, I will have to limit my trips,''  
said Lewis, a software trainer from Stamford. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts and representatives of the petroleum industry say they  
cannot predict whether prices could go up again before Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been a variety of reasons offered for the rising  
price at the pump -- improving economies in Asia, the Organization 
of the Petroleum Exporting Countries' plan to cut crude oil 
production and refinery explosions on the West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Some motorists aren't buying any of it.  
</P>
<P>
	``The claims of a shortage are not true. It doesn't seem to me  
that we're going to run out of gas,'' said Paul Caston, a computer 
consultant from Chicago who filled up his rental car in Stamford. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute, which represents about 400 oil  
companies, said increases in crude oil costs are behind the 
increases at the pumps. In December, refiners were paying an 
average of $9.84 per barrel. Now, they are paying close to $20 per 
barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Planting, an analyst for the institute, said there also is a  
seasonal factor. When demand is weaker in January, prices tend to 
be lower. As demand increases in the summer months, prices tend to 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the price increases, AAA said most motorists are not  
expected to curb their travel plans for the holiday weekend. The 
association is predicting that nearly 34.8 million Americans will 
travel 100 miles or more during the weekend, an increase of 2 
percent over last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't think at this level that we're talking about  
people being discouraged or willing to forego that trip because of 
where the gas price stands today,'' spokesman Jerry Cheske said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one motorist agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not to a point where it's prohibitive,'' said Dr. Jan  
Kaplowitz, a retired chiropractor. ``In different parts of the 
world, they pay a lot more for gas.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
