<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Expected To Hit Bahamas  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis buffeted fragile  
Bahamian islands with gusty winds today and is threatening to 
strengthen into a major storm that could imperil the eastern 
seaboard of the United States by Sunday. The U.S. National Weather 
Center predicted today the hurricane will hit the northern Bahamas 
tomorrow morning. From hundreds of miles away, Dennis is kicking up 
waves off the Outer Banks of North Carolina, prompting the governor 
to put state troopers on alert. National Guard troops are preparing 
for storm duty in South Carolina and a hurricane watch has been 
posted for Florida's east coast. 

</P>
<P>
	Venezuela Opposition Defies Closure  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Opposition lawmakers today broke  
through crowds and climbed over the capitol building's fence in 
defiance of a constitutional assembly's order that virtually shut 
Congress down. Police and the National Guard fired tear gas and 
water cannons to control clashes between supporters and opponents 
of President Hugo Chavez. Six people were injured. Chavez, a former 
paratrooper who led a failed 1992 coup attempt, says a major 
shakeup of Venezuela's institutions in needed to root out some of 
the world's worst political corruption. 

</P>
<P>
	Board Issues Gulf Illness Report  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A presidential oversight board concluded today  
there is no evidence to link mysterious Gulf War illnesses to 
exposure to depleted uranium used in U.S. munitions. In so finding, 
the Special Oversight Board on Gulf War Illness joined conclusions 
reached in other studies. In an interim report, the presidential 
panel issued recommendations designed to keep better track of those 
with diagnosed and undiagnosed Gulf War illnesses. But the panel 
shed little new light on the causes of the diseases. A final report 
is due in May. 

</P>
<P>
	Mir Crew Prepares To Head Home  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The crew of the Mir space station prepared today  
to head back to Earth and leave the orbiter unmanned in 
preparations for its abandonment next year. Russian cosmonauts 
Viktor Afanasyev and Sergei Avdeyev, along with French astronaut 
Jean-Pierre Haignere, are scheduled to move from the station to the 
Soyuz escape capsule today. The decision to abandon the 13-year-old 
Mir came after the government decided to stop financing its 
operation. Attempts to attract private funds failed. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Upbeat on Mideast Accord  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met  
today with two senior Palestinian officials and gave an upbeat 
account of talks with Israel on a timetable for a West Bank 
pullback. ``We are looking forward to the conclusion of this aspect 
of the peace process,'' she said, standing outside her home with 
negotiator Saeb Erekat and Yasser Arafat's deputy, Mahmoud Abbas. 
The agreement taking shape calls for Israel to resume a pullback 
from 13 percent of the West Bank that was halted after 2 percent 
was surrendered. Israel would give up 7 percent in October and the 
final 4 percent in January. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew  
</P>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton golfed with Prince  
Andrew today and jokingly bet the island of Martha's Vineyard on 
the outcome. Clinton and the Duke of York teed off at Farm Neck 
Golf Club where the president, with the prince as a passenger, 
stopped his golf cart in front of reporters and introduced his 
royal guest. The Clintons are scheduled to leave Martha's Vineyard 
tomorrow for a round of fund-raisers in the Hamptons district of 
eastern Long Island. 

</P>
<P>
	Personal Income Rises in July  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' income crept up in July, while  
consumer spending rose faster but not at the frenzied pace of 
earlier this year. The Commerce Department said today that personal 
income rose a slower-than-expected 0.2 percent last month, the 
smallest gain this year. Because consumer spending has repeatedly 
outpaced incomes, the nation's savings rate has set a string of 
record lows this year, with the lowest a negative 1.5 percent in 
May. In July, the savings rate was better: minus 1.4 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 15; Nasdaq Gains 10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 15.52 points at 11,182.93. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 1,603-1,129. The Nasdaq was up 10.18 
at 2,784.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Phenix City 3, Toms River 2  
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Phenix City, Ala., regrouped after an  
overnight rain delay and rallied today to defeat defending champion 
Toms River, N.J., 3-2 in the U.S. championship game at the Little 
League World Series. Phenix City will play Osaka, Japan, at 4:30 
p.m. EDT tomorrow for the title. In a game that was suspended by 
rain last night, Bryan Woodall pitched five innings of shutout ball 
and struck out eight for the win. Some of Toms River's players wept 
in the dugout. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
