<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Looms East of Bahamas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis loomed east of the  
Bahamian capital of Nassau today, marooning some vacationers, 
increasing the peril for Florida and threatening to strike South 
Carolina as a major storm. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of the Bahamas expanded a hurricane warning to  
cover much of the northwest Bahamas. Dennis was packing 80 mph 
winds as it moved west-northwest at 7 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. National Weather Center predicted today the hurricane  
would hit the northern Bahamas on Saturday morning. It urged 
Bahamians to rush their preparations to protect life and property. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, the National Hurricane Center put the east  
coast of Florida on hurricane watch and urged coastal residents 
from central Florida up to North Carolina to watch the storm 
carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	A weather system that was supposed to steer Dennis away from the  
Florida coast had not. At 2 p.m. EDT, Dennis was centered about 335 
miles southeast of Cape Canaveral, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not letting anyone off the hook anywhere along the  
coast,'' said another meteorologist at the center, Todd Kimberlain. 
</P>
<P>
	Although forecasters had been talking about a glancing blow for  
the U.S. mainland, hurricane center director Jerry Jarrell said 
Dennis could make a direct hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ups the ante a little bit for central Florida,'' said  
Jarrell. ``It's too close for comfort right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis was expected to strengthen over the next 24 hours and  
bring five to 10 inches of rain and tides 3 to 6 feet above normal. 
</P>
<P>
	``People still remember Hurricane Andrew here from 1992, so  
we're keeping an eye out for it,'' hotel owner Harcourt Cambridge 
said in the Bahamian capital of Nassau. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew blew off much of the topsoil on Eleuthera island, where  
some trees had only just begun bearing fruit again, said Gilbert 
Kemp, local government chairman at Hatchet Bay. Eleuthera is a 
110-mile-long strip of pink sand where 8,000 people live. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemp said it had rained through the night and the wind was  
picking up, bending some smaller trees, as residents rushed to 
board up their homes. Boats in Nassau were hauled out of the 
harbor, and the governor general's official residence was boarded 
up before a light rain started falling Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis kicked up surf in the Carolinas, where people began  
stocking up on storm supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, Gov. Jim Hodges ordered 1,000 National Guard  
troops and 500 state troopers to prepare for duty, but no decision 
has been made on any possible coastal evacuation. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, emergency planners urged 150,000 coastal  
residents to get ready for the storm. State troopers and emergency 
management personnel were on alert. 
</P>
<P>
	While surfers off the Outer Banks rode huge waves generated by  
the far-off storm, some residents of the Wilmington, N.C. area went 
to supply stores for plywood, batteries and lanterns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're starting to sell plywood and a lot of propane,  
batteries, lights,'' said Troy Green, a clerk at a Carolina Beach 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, the approaching storm prompted many surfers to play  
hooky from work and school today to catch some unseasonably good 
waves. 
</P>
<P>
	``On my way in this morning, I was following someone that had  
two or three boards on their car,'' said Heather Lewis, marking 
director for Ron Jon Surf Shop on Cocoa Beach, about 40 miles east 
of Orlando. The shop has been getting deluged with calls for surf 
reports, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis became a hurricane late Wednesday as its winds reached 75  
mph. Forecasters said it could strengthen. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other nearby storms posed little threat, forecasters said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cindy, upgraded to a hurricane again late Wednesday, was far out  
in the Atlantic. And Emily -- which sprang up at near-hurricane 
strength Tuesday -- began to lose strength and was downgraded to a 
tropical depression. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
