<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Illinois St. Player Going to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) -- The one Illinois State football player  
to stand trial for a 1998 fraternity house brawl has been found 
guilty and faces a minimum sentence of six years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Ramsey, 23, was convicted of two counts of home invasion  
and one count of mob action in a bench trial Thursday before 
Circuit Judge G. Michael Prall. The home invasion charge carries a 
prison sentence of 6-to-30 year. The minimum sentence for mob 
action also is six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey, a defensive halfback, sobbed audibly after Prall  
announced the verdict. He will be sentenced Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ramsey led a group of 30 to 40 current and  
former ISU football players who broke into the Sigma Alpha Epsilon 
fraternity house on March 22, 1998. He was among eight players 
accused of attacking about 40 fraternity members in retaliation for 
a fight the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said as many as six fraternity members were injured  
in the fracas. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey's attorney, Paul Welch, said it was ``horribly  
inappropriate'' that no fraternity members involved in the fight on 
March 21 were charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges were dropped against football player Aveion Cason this  
June due to insufficient evidence. Robert Boyd, who pleaded guilty 
to misdemeanor battery, received 24 months' probation and was 
ordered to pay a share of $9,000 in restitution to fraternity 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Five other players who earlier pleaded guilty to more serious  
charges were sentenced to 90 days in the McLean County Jail and 
also ordered to pay restitution. 
</P>
<P>
	McLean County Assistant State's Attorney Michael Stroh said  
Ramsey's punishment would send a message to those who chose to take 
the law into their own hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are proper ways to deal with conflict, and the path that  
Kenneth Ramsey and the other members of the football team chose 
that night was the wrong path,'' Stroh said. ``We cannot have 
citizens exacting retribution on their own -- vigilantism.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
