<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton golfed with royalty  
Friday and jokingly staked the island of Martha's Vineyard on the 
outcome. The game was rained out before he had a chance to win or 
lose. 
</P>
<P>
	The president joined Britain's Prince Andrew, the duke of York,  
on the links at the Farm Neck Golf Club. He noted that in the 17th 
century the ground on which they stood -- indeed all of this island 
off the Massachusetts coast -- was owned by the dukes of York. 
</P>
<P>
	Prince Andrew has held the title since his mother, Queen  
Elizabeth, conferred it in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what the bet is? If he beats me, we have to give him  
back the island,'' Clinton said, stopping his golf cart near a 
gaggle of reporters and photographers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you want the island back, sir,'' a reporter shouted.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you when I've won,'' said the grinning prince, a  
passenger in the president's electric cart. 
</P>
<P>
	But neither the prince nor the president won before a heavy,  
steady rain turned the course to puddles. The party quit on the 
15th fairway, and the prince soon splashed across the parking lot 
toward a black Land Rover. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked the game's outcome, Andrew pulled a crumpled wad of  
American bills from his pocket and replied: ``I have still got a 
little money in my pocket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the question of the ownership of Martha's Vineyard hadn't  
been settled by the American Revolution, its 14,000 permanent 
residents and the scores of thousands of vacationers who visit each 
autumn might have had reason for worry: 
</P>
<P>
	The prince's first shot sailed down the middle of the fairway;  
the president's veered radically off course. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't go way over there,'' he implored.  
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, with the ball still in the air, there was a loud  
crash. A staff member in the nearby clubhouse had dropped a tub of 
dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton usually gives himself the luxury of a mulligan or two  
when he tees off, taking advantage of the extra shots that some 
golfers grant their partners. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the prince made do with his initial shot, Clinton  
followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was evidently played without handicap.  
</P>
<P>
	``No strokes. ... All flat,'' Prince Andrew decreed.  
</P>
<P>
	The royal golf match was the highlight of Clinton's last full  
vacation day on Martha's Vineyard, the seventh time he has spent 
summer weeks here during his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	The vacation's second half will be at the Finger Lakes region of  
upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton are set to  
leave Saturday for the posh Hamptons region of Long Island for a 
series of fund-raisers intended to raise money for Democratic 
campaigns in general and for Mrs. Clinton's likely New York Senate 
campaign in particular. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night at East Hampton the Clintons are hosts at the  
airport terminal to a buffet reception of the young Democrats' 
``Saxophone Club.'' At $250 per person, some 800 people are 
expected to turn out for the Clintons and comedian Jon Stewart to 
net about $200,000 for the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, it's on to a $1,000 per plate barbecue dinner at a  
private East Hampton residence. Singer Phoebe Snow will entertain 
the 300 people contributing jointly to the DNC, Mrs. Clinton's 
anticipated Senate race and the Democratic Senatorial Campaign 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the Clintons star at a $5,000 per person lunch for 80  
at a South Hampton home. The first $1,000 of every ticket price, a 
party official said, will go to Mrs. Clinton's race with the 
remainder being shared by the DNC and DSCC. 
</P>
<P>
	In the priciest of the galas, rocker Jon Bon Jovi provides the  
music at a Bridgehampton dinner on Sunday night solely benefiting 
the DNC. At $25,000 per couple, the event is expected to bag 
$900,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes worked Friday to  
cram the airwaves at Skaneateles Lake, the Clintons' final stop on 
their half-recreational, half-political tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forbes campaign bought five days' worth of spots on three  
Skaneateles-area radio stations in upstate New York -- WSYR, WSEN 
and WNSS -- to hammer at the president's opposition to Republican 
tax cuts legislation pending in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sign the tax cut, Mr. President,'' Forbes says in the ad. ``I  
would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the American Conservative Union purchased television time  
in the upstate region to criticize Clinton's decision to offer 
clemency to 16 Puerto Rican militants. Those ads are scheduled to 
run next Monday through Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
