<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Teen's Shooting Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Justice Department has reopened an  
investigation into the 1994 shooting death of a 16-year-old Hasidic 
student following would-be Senate candidate Hillary Rodham 
Clinton's interest in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron Halberstam was killed and three other people were wounded  
when Lebanese immigrant Rashid Baz opened fire on a van filled with 
Jewish students on the Brooklyn Bridge. The shooting was in 
apparent retaliation for the slayings of 29 Muslims in a West Bank 
mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	The slain youth's mother, Devorah Halberstam, has led members of  
the Hasidic community in urging the case be reopened, both to seek 
other suspects and to explore whether it could be prosecuted under 
federal civil rights or terrorism statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement by the office of U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White and the  
FBI attributed the decision to reopen the case to requests from the 
Halberstam family, U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer and Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	But White House spokesman Joe Lockhart confirmed today that Mrs.  
Clinton also had expressed interest in the case. He said the first 
lady asked a staffer to inquire ``if it was appropriate for some 
kind of meeting to take place'' about the case. 
</P>
<P>
	He said she asked her staffers to relay the question to the  
office of White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, and he passed it 
on to the Justice Department, telling staffers to handle the matter 
as they saw fit. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of further investigation has been important to some  
members of New York's Jewish community -- a key voting bloc. Playing 
a role in reopening the case could be a political plus for Mrs. 
Clinton and Giuliani; both are considering a run for the U.S. 
Senate from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Baz is already serving a life sentence for the crime. He was  
convicted on state charges by a jury that rejected his claim that 
he opened fire because he was having a flashback to his troubled 
past in war-torn Lebanon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
