<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suit by Family of 'Marlboro Man' OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARSHALL, Texas (AP) -- A federal judge has refused to dismiss a  
lawsuit against the tobacco industry by the family of the actor who 
appeared for years as the Marlboro Man. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 lawsuit by Lilo McLean, wife of David McLean, named  
several tobacco companies, including Marlboro cigarette maker 
Philip Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	The case, which seeks unspecified damages, alleges that every  
cigarette maker in the United States conspired to hide facts 
regarding the addictive nature of nicotine. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McLean says her husband suffered from emphysema in the late  
1980s because of his nicotine addiction and later was stricken with 
lung cancer. David McLean died in October 1995 at age 73. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants asked U.S. District Judge David Folsom to throw  
the case out, saying Texas law doesn't allow for lawsuits involving 
addiction. But Folsom refused in an Aug. 13 ruling, said Don 
Howarth, a Los Angeles attorney representing the McLean family. 
</P>
<P>
	Folsom certified his ruling for immediate appeal to the Fifth  
Circuit Court of Appeals. If the appeals court upholds the ruling, 
trial could begin early next year, plaintiffs attorneys said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco industry representatives couldn't immediately be reached  
for comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	David McLean began his role as the rugged Marlboro pitchman in  
the early 1960s, shortly before the U.S. Surgeon General's 1964 
order that cigarettes be labeled with health warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the labels warning that the product ``might be  
dangerous to your health'' were printed, he had been smoking for 
more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims that David McLean sometimes smoked five packs  
of cigarettes while posing for a single commercial. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 07:10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parents of White Supremacist Puzzled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The parents of a white supremacist who killed two  
and injured nine others during a two-state rampage said their son 
grew up in a loving, diverse environment that belied his racist 
views. 
</P>
<P>
	In their first public statement since their son's Fourth of July  
weekend shooting spree and suicide, Kenneth and Beverly Smith said 
their 21-year-old son, Benjamin, was raised in a household where 
they ``had friends from diverse racial and religious groups.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the couple said he severed ties with the family and  
they were unable to contact him for two months before the 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very painful to first lose him to a viewpoint we found  
abhorrent and then lose him in such a horrible and final way,'' the 
couple said. 
</P>
<P>
	They said they have searched in vain for an explanation for the  
shootings. All the victims were members of minority groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like the parents of other good children who became criminal,  
alcoholic, drug-addicted or mentally ill, we found no answer,'' the 
couple said. ``We were loving parents to Benjamin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not share or understand the beliefs our son adopted  
near the end of his life,'' the couple said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting spree began July 2 in the Chicago area. Smith  
killed Ricky Byrdsong, a former Northwestern University basketball 
coach, wounded six Orthodox Jews and shot at an Asian-American 
couple, who were not hit. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 3, Smith fired at Asians and blacks in three other  
Illinois cities, Springfield, Decatur and Urbana, wounding three 
people. On July 4, Smith killed Won-Joon Yoon, an Asian student, in 
Bloomington, Ind. Smith had attended college in both Urbana and 
Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	Later that day, Smith shot himself while struggling with police  
attempting to arrest him in Salem, Ill. On Thursday, a Marion 
County coroner's jury formally ruled that Smith's death was a 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Autopsy results read to the jury revealed that Smith shot  
himself once in the chin with a .38-caliber pistol, then used a 
.22-caliber handgun to shoot himself in the chest and thigh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
