<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher Friday, with gains  
in the automotive industry leading the way. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed 0.48  
points higher at 315.02, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, 
which tracks 297 companies in countries joining the single 
currency, ended 0.76 points better at 329.97. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 0.95 points to 3,853.48,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index gained 5.89 points to end at 3,789.64. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, the Paris CAC 40 index rose 0.3 percent to  
4,642.71, with supermarket groups Promodes and Carrefour showing 
gains in anticipation of strong first half earnings due next week 
and speculation that the two may merge. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed 0.6 percent higher to  
5,420.36, helped by gains in the automotive sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen rose 1.25 euros to 58.49 euros, and BMW gained 1.15  
euros to close at 30.05 euros. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers elsewhere in Europe also posted gains. Volvo ended  
3.7 percent higher, and truck maker Scania -- which is being bought 
by Volvo -- ended up 1.1 percent. Peugot and Fiat also posted 
moderate gains. 
</P>
<P>
	London's FTSE 100 index rose 0.1 percent to 6,375.20, with Reed  
International, the British arm of publishing group Reed-Elsevier, 
the best performer. Reed gained 6.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsevier, the Dutch arm of Reed-Elsevier, rose 4.3 percent,  
while Amsterdam's AEX index ended 0.2 percent lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Zurich's Swiss Market Index rose 0.4 percent to 7,167.70, but  
Swisscom fell 2 percent even though it posted a 6 percent rise in 
half-year net profit and forecast a strong full-year performance, 
despite anticipated higher costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chemicals group Clariant fell 1.5 percent after it said full  
year sales fell 8.6 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
