<HEADLINE> Storm Disrupts Amtrak Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Passenger rail service on Amtrak's Northeast  
Corridor was shut down between Washington and Baltimore for several 
hours because of track flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak spokesman Russ Hall said trains were delayed from around  
9 p.m. Thursday until midnight after up to six inches of rain, and 
then mud, covered the rails about two miles south of Baltimore's 
Penn Station. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said 14 trains were affected. The last southbound train,  
No. 177, arrived in Washington at 1:59 a.m. today, 48 minutes 
behind schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was worse news for some passengers traveling north.  
Hall said train No. 66, due in Boston at 6:55 a.m., was five hours 
behind schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Some trains were held at Washington's Union Station and in  
stations north of Baltimore. But other trains were stopped on the 
tracks, where passengers had to wait for hours before they began 
moving again. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said the bad weather made it impossible to get buses to  
transport the stranded passengers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
