<HEADLINE> Texas Claims Fassero Off Waivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Struggling Jeff Fassero, who has allowed a major  
league-high 34 home runs, was traded from the Seattle Mariners to 
the Texas Rangers on Friday for a minor league player to be named. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know its been a rough year for him, but a change of scenery  
sometimes does wonders for a veteran,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 36-year-old left-hander was 4-14 with a 7.38 ERA in 30 games  
for Seattle, allowing 123 runs and 188 hits in 139 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	He won 13 or more games each year from 1995-98.  
</P>
<P>
	``He did well the past couple of years for us,'' Mariners  
manager Lou Piniella said. ``This year, he struggled. I'm not sure 
why. He was healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas has struggled against left-handed hitters, allowing 76  
homers, the league's third-highest total. Lefties are hitting .283 
against the Rangers, the sixth-highest average in the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	Lefty batters are hitting .252 (32-for-127) against Fassero this  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a lot of success against left-handers this year,''  
Oates said. ``The last time we saw him he had a decent fastball, 
and a good split-finger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oates said Fassero would pitch out of the bullpen, but hinted he  
may join the starting rotation in a week. Oates has thought about 
removing right-hander Mike Morgan (12-8, 6.11 ERA) from the 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle called up left-hander Robert Ramsay from Tacoma to take  
Fassero's spot on the roster. Ramsay, 25, was acquired from the 
Boston Red Sox on July 26 and immediately optioned to Tacoma. He 
made five starts with the Rainiers, going 4-1 with a 1.08 ERA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
