<HEADLINE> Moiseyev Confident at Yonkers Trot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- Racing from the outside is nothing new to  
Jack Moiseyev, and that's why the veteran driver is confident that 
Raffaello Ambrosio can win the $273,891 Yonkers Trot on Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-year-old bay colt by Victory Dream-Tishes Dishes drew the  
seven hole in the eight-horse race that is the second leg of the 
Triple Crown for trotters. With a 3-3-2 record in 10 outings this 
year, Ambrosio is the second choice to C R Renegade, which drew the 
No. 6 post position. 
</P>
<P>
	``On a half-mile track you just have to play it by ear when you  
are that far on the outside,'' said Moiseyev. ``My horse has done 
well the last couple of outings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moiseyev was referring to a fourth-place finish in the  
Hambletonian, the opening leg of the Triple Crown in which Ambrosio 
left from No. 10. He also was referring to a Yonkers Trot 
elimination victory in 2:00 flat after leaving from the outside in 
the five-horse race. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Guerflein, trainer of Raffaello Ambrosio and also Self  
Possessed, which set a world record of 1:51 3-5 in capturing the 
Hambo, is a bit on the pessimistic side. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're leaving from too far out,'' said Guerfein, who opted to  
enter Self Possessed in the American National at Balmoral, Crete, 
Ill., Saturday night rather than go for the triple crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``C R Renegade will probably go first over, so we'll find out  
how good a trotter Raffaello Ambrosio is,'' Guerfein said. ``I was 
extremely confident until the draw. Still, he has an excellent 
chance to win his first major stakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rod Allen, who is driving C R Renegade for his father, Carl, the  
owner, said: ``He was headstrong in winning his elimination (1:59 
3-5). When I tried to get something out of him, he ran. 
</P>
<P>
	``C R Renegade is a real determined horse. What makes him so  
nice is that he is so easy to drive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yonkers elimination was the second straight win for the  
brown colt by Troubador-Country Kay and boosted his record to 7-3-1 
in 14 outings with winnings of $415,184 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Hambletonian, the 3-year-old was a badly beaten ninth,  
but Allen said, ``That was just a bad trip. I've forgotten about it 
and now am ready to keep our comeback going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Little Brown Jug on Sept. 23 in Delaware, Ohio, completes  
the Triple Crown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
