<HEADLINE> Wheat Falls, Soybeans Rise / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures retreated in early trading today on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, while corn futures were mixed and 
soybeans edged higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by concerns about insufficient  
export sales to help reduce relatively large inventories. With 
Canada's competing crop expected to be larger than originally 
forecast, investors are concerned U.S. export sales will suffer. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures were mixed amid uncertainty about the impending  
harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were buoyed by continued market talk that China is  
looking to buy some of the U.S. crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 2 cents to $2.81 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn was unchanged at $2.15 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 
1/4 cent to $1.14 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to 
$4.68 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose 0.22 cent to 66.57 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose 0.18 cent to 79.35 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs rose 0.05 cent to 45.20 cents a pound; February 
pork bellies rose 1.4 cents to 58.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
