<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Census Count May Have Missed Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Whether it's building schools or day care  
centers, locating clinics or distributing money for school lunches 
and Head Start, if the government doesn't know where the children 
are it can't provide the right amount of aid. 
</P>
<P>
	And billions of dollars in programs have been misallocated over  
the past decade because children were missed in the 1990 Census at 
twice the overall rate, a children's advocacy group contended 
Thursday. They pressed for an added emphasis on counting children 
in next year's census. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1990 head count missed 3.2 percent of children -- double the  
1.6 percent overall undercount -- with the rate climbing to 4.5 
percent in four states where thousands were overlooked. 
</P>
<P>
	William P. O'Hare of the Annie E. Casey Foundation's Kids Count  
Project said the undercount rate was 4.5 percent in Texas, Florida, 
Louisiana and Mississippi, the worst in the nation among the 
states. The District of Columbia's undercount rate was 6.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island came closest to counting all its youngsters,  
missing just 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Census Bureau earlier reported that about half of the  
4 million people missed nationwide in 1990 were children, O'Hare 
refined bureau data to calculate the rate for each state. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Census Bureau expects it to be even more difficult to  
count children next year, because the population includes more 
minorities, more foster children, more children in unstable living 
arrangements and more non-English-speaking families, O'Hare said. 
</P>
<P>
	Census numbers are used to determine how much federal money each  
state should get for a variety of programs. O'Hare noted that the 
General Accounting Office -- an investigative agency of Congress -- 
has estimated that the undercount cost Texas $1 billion and 
California perhaps $2 billion over the course of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Hare noted that in 1998, Census data were used in distributing  
$3.7 billion for foster care programs, $3 billion in women's, 
infants and children's food programs, and $1 billion in block 
grants for child care development. 
</P>
<P>
	Also affected are funds for such things as school lunch  
programs, Head Start classes, school construction, hiring teachers, 
establishing local day care and public transit programs for 
parents, said Jacqueline J. Byers, director of research for the 
National Association of Counties. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the children are missed, how will we know they're there so  
we can target the programs?'' asked Byers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Henderson of the National Education Association said  
failing to count children results in overcrowded classrooms: ``If 
we don't know how many children live in a community, we cannot 
provide adequate school facilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both urged parents, teachers and others to stress the need for  
cooperation with next year's Census so everyone, including 
children, will be counted. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line, said Terri Ann Lowenthal of the Census 2000  
Initiative, is that because of the undercount, billions of dollars 
are misdirected away from states and communities that need it. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Hare, whose group advocates for children, said there are many  
reasons children are missed more often than adults. Foster children 
may not be listed on a temporary caregiver's census form, divorced 
parents may each think the other listed the children on their 
census form, grandparents may not include children staying with 
them, many immigrant families fear providing information to the 
government and many worry the landlord will learn how many people 
are in one apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	Census day is next April 1 and the effort has been mired in  
political wrangling over how it will be done. The Supreme Court 
ruled in January that a direct count must be conducted for purposes 
of redistributing seats in the House of Representatives among the 
states, but said modern statistical methods should be used to 
produce more accurate counts for other uses. 
</P>
<P>
	That means there will be two sets of numbers produced, boosting  
the count's cost from the previous estimate of $4 billion to as 
much as $6 billion, Census officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Establishment of some 500 local offices is already under way, as  
are recruiting efforts for the estimated 860,000 temporary workers 
who will be hired to make the count. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
