<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Approves Ted Parker Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) -- A federal bankruptcy judge has approved  
the $90 million sale of the majority of Ted Parker Home Sales Inc. 
to Champion Enterprises, the nation's largest mobile home maker and 
Ted Parker's main supplier. 
</P>
<P>
	The approval came Thursday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in  
Wilmington, Del., and means hundreds of Ted Parker Homes customers 
may soon be able to complete their sales or request refunds of 
deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	Champion, based in Auburn Hills, Mich., will buy back all  
Champion inventory owned by Ted Parker Homes and its sister 
company, Carolina Home Sales Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Champion has also agreed to buy the leases of 37 of Ted Parker  
Homes' 42 retail centers in North Carolina, South Carolina and 
Mississippi. The company may eventually buy the leases of the 
remaining five sales lots as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Ted Parker and Carolina Home Sales filed for Chapter 11  
bankruptcy protection on July 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Katz, director of reorganization for Ted Parker Home Sales,  
said the sale also may help about 400 Ted Parker Home Sales 
employees laid off two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with both companies expect the sale to be completed  
next week. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 20:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Authorities Rule Against BNP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French banking authorities ruled early Saturday  
that hostile bidder Banque Nationale de Paris cannot keep its stake 
in its unwilling target, Societe Generale, effectively ending BNP's 
hopes of creating Europe's largest bank in terms of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the six-month-long takeover fight may not be over since  
BNP can still contest the ruling with France's highest 
administrative court, the Council of State. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taking into account the results of the takeover bid offer, BNP  
``doesn't hold in a patent manner an effective power of control 
over Societe Generale,'' the Committee of Credit and Investment 
Institutions said in a statement following a marathon 11-hour 
meeting that began Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``In these conditions, the committee decided ... not to  
authorize BNP to hold a stake representing 31.8 percent of voting 
rights in Societe Generale,'' the CECEI said. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking watchdog, headed by Bank of France Governor  
Jean-Claude Trichet, said the ruling came after intense efforts to 
broker a negotiated outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, BNP launched a two-pronged $37 billion hostile  
takeover bid offer for Societe Generale and Paribas, which were in 
the midst of merging their operations to create a banking giant 
called SG-Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP won control of Paribas, though it garnered only a 37.1  
percent stake -- and 31.8 percent of the voting rights -- in Societe 
Generale, leaving the outcome with the regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The CECEI had said that it would intervene in the stock market  
battle if a bank fail to gain 50.01 percent of the voting rights in 
its target. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision allowing BNP to keep its stake would have allowed BNP  
to move further toward its goal of a three-way merger. 
</P>
<P>
	French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn, interviewed on  
French television late Friday, took a neutral stance on the 
takeover battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever the outcome will be, it'll be a good thing for French  
economy,'' Strauss-Kahn said on TF1 television. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP had claimed it had enough shares for effective control over  
Societe Generale. But Societe Generale had vigorously opposed BNP, 
saying its hostile suitor would not have the authority to make 
major decisions for the bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
