<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Helping Drought in East Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- It will take more than a few rain showers to  
satiate the parched East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Green grass, budding trees and sudden rain over the past few  
weeks are only disguising a lingering, nasty dry spell. It's so bad 
that forecasters say the best solution might be a couple of 
hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	``A drought is not something that we can say, `Hey, it's rained,  
now it's over,''' said Mark Tobin, a meteorologist with the private 
forecaster AccuWeather. ``A drought is a big huge monster that 
slowly develops over time, and slowly goes away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainfall has edged closer to normal this month for most of the  
East, but remains 6 inches to 13 inches below normal for the year, 
the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials and meteorologists say it would take several  
weeks of above-average rainfall to repair current water levels -- 
and to beat the drought, it would take several months of good rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dennis or another other tropical storm could prove  
welcome rainmakers, should they trek through mid-Atlantic and 
Northeast states as they weaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hopeful that these couple of hurricanes will bring us  
some rain,'' said Bob Will, a commissioner in Pennsylvania's 
drought-stricken Somerset County. Forecasters say the storm's path 
is far from certain, and it might not hit land at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the bad news continues to mount.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal agriculture officials on Thursday declared North  
Carolina a drought disaster area, joining Kentucky, West Virginia, 
Delaware, Massachusetts and South Carolina. Similar disaster 
declarations have been issued in parts of six western states and 16 
states east of the Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	This despite soaking rains in some areas.  
</P>
<P>
	In central and eastern North Carolina, a thunderstorm packing  
65-mph winds overturned a trailer, threw a storage building onto a 
car and damaged three planes at the Craven County airport. No one 
was injured in the storm, which dumped 2 1/2 inches of rain at the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	While 3 inches of heavy rain tangled the commute in New York  
City on Thursday, the city was still 6 inches below normal for the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland is still inches short of being out of drought  
conditions, even though 7 inches of rain fell Wednesday in Anne 
Arundel County, Md., and up to 8 inches more poured onto the 
Baltimore area Thursday. The storms left 49,000 people without 
power and almost 14,000 were still affected this morning. Flooding 
also shut down part of the MARC commuter service between Baltimore 
and Washington today. 
</P>
<P>
	Marci Smit of Columbia, Md., said her family sacrificed their  
lawn to save water. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand that we have to do our part,'' Smit said. ``It's  
been looking pretty sad, but ... in the last week, it has started 
to green up a bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It rained hard in parts of New Jersey this week, but state  
officials say they aren't yet ready to ease water restrictions 
imposed Aug. 6 
</P>
<P>
	Some parts of Pennsylvania have received up to 8 inches of rain  
this month. On Thursday night, thunderstorms raked across the 
southeastern part of the state, causing local flooding and power 
outages. Rainfall amounts as high as 4 inches were reported in a 
few locations and more than 18,000 homes were without power this 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the Susquehanna River is at its lowest point ever,  
western Pennsylvania rivers are being artificially maintained by 
the Army Corps of Engineers and most water suppliers are within a 
few weeks of rationing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hasn't rained enough,'' said Marko Bourne, a spokesman for  
the state Emergency Management Agency. ``We're trying to erase a 
12-month-plus rainfall deficit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the scattered heavy rains are ``a little late,'' said  
Abe Harpster, whose corn crop feeds a 2,000-cow dairy herd in 
south-central Pennsylvania. Many neighbors have already cut their 
stunted corn and the final growth of hay -- if there was any. 
</P>
<P>
	Harpster's farm received more than 3 1/2 inches of rain last week  
and another inch on Thursday afternoon. ``It's helping,'' Harpster 
said. ``But a lot of the damage has been done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the recent showers left him somewhat optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every great drought is followed by great rains,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
