<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Said To Oppose FALN Leniency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal law enforcement agencies opposed  
leniency for 16 imprisoned Puerto Rican militants in the weeks 
before President Clinton offered to commute their sentences, The 
New York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The clemency petition for the independence activists was flatly  
opposed by the FBI, the Bureau of Prisons and federal prosecutors 
in Illinois and Connecticut, according to government officials who 
spoke to the Times on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking from the Clinton's vacation spot on Martha's Vineyard,  
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said today, ``All views 
were presented to the president fully and completely and were taken 
into consideration before making the final decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton offered clemency on Aug. 11 to 16 members of the FALN, a  
Spanish acronym for Armed Forces of National Liberation, in 
response to requests from human rights officials who argued that 
their sentences, ranging from 15 years to 90 years, were too harsh. 
The offer came with conditions: that the militants sign statements 
requesting commutation, renounce violence and abide by all 
conditions of release set by law or the Parole Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The FALN members were convicted in a series of bombing attacks  
on U.S. civilian and military targets staged from 1974 to 1983. 
Twelve were convicted in Illinois and four in Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Six people were killed and dozens -- including several New York  
police officers -- were wounded in attacks attributed to the group. 
But those offered clemency were not directly involved in attacks 
that resulted in deaths. None of the 16 has yet accepted the 
president's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The imprisoned members of the nationalist group are considered  
political prisoners by many Puerto Ricans. 
</P>
<P>
	In their recommendations, FBI officials complained about  
granting leniency to members of a militant group that had claimed 
responsibility for terrorist acts at a time when the United States 
was engaged in a worldwide battle against terrorism, the Times 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Bureau of Prisons concluded that if militants  
were released, they might resume their activism, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Republican speculation that Clinton may have acted now  
to help his wife, Hillary, court New York's Puerto Rican vote for 
her possible U.S. Senate bid, Lockart said he was unaware of the 
first lady being involved in any way. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
