<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Support Dwindles for Black Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite a history of inflammatory speech,  
Khallid Abdul Muhammad found the doors to some of Harlem's most 
treasured institutions open to him in the days before last year's 
Million Youth March. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Nation of Islam spokesman held meetings at Sylvia's  
soul food restaurant and press conferences at the Abyssinian 
Baptist Church, the historic center of Harlem's spiritual and 
political life. Many of Harlem's politicians were reluctant to 
denounce an event dedicated to black and Latino youth. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, many of those doors have been slammed shut.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 rally attracted a fraction of the 200,000 people  
Muhammad had hoped for and featured dozens of speakers who 
excoriated Jews and whites. It ended with 28 injuries when police 
in riot gear approached the stage and Muhammad exhorted the 
audience to beat or shoot officers who threatened them. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that September day when Muhammad was hustled off stage by  
his personal security team, Harlem leaders say he has rarely been 
seen in the community and has done little to build grass-roots 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	When Muhammad held a news conference this week to announce plans  
for a second Million Youth March on Labor Day weekend, the event 
was not held at the Abyssinian Baptist Church but on the sidewalk 
outside the Apollo Theatre. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Muhammad's backing is at such a low ebb that politicians  
who had been reluctant to criticize him for fear of alienating 
segments of the black community have been taking very public shots 
at him. 
</P>
<P>
	``This march shouldn't take place in Harlem or anywhere but  
hell, and Khallid can go down there with it,'' said City Councilman 
Bill Perkins, who has surfaced as Muhammad's most outspoken critic 
in the black community. ``There is no support for it. Period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We would rather not have the march through the streets of  
Harlem. We don't want that again,'' said Stanley Gleaton, the 
president of the local community board. 
</P>
<P>
	Muhammad is also locked in another battle with City Hall. The  
city has again denied him a permit to march and Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani has repeatedly called it a ``hate march.'' Last year's 
march took place only after organizers went to federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys representing Muhammad say they will return to federal  
court again to win the right to march down Malcolm X Boulevard on 
Sept. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Muhammad this week vowed to march anyway, declaring that ``no  
devil, racist, cantankerous, constipated cracker like Mayor 
Giuliani can stop (the march).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The obstacles against Muhammad are formidable: Nearly every  
elected official who represents Harlem, from Perkins and Gleaton to 
U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel, has denounced him. Many residents and 
business owners in the neighborhood say another march would cause 
too many disruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're saying it's a waste of time for people to come out,''  
said Rangel. 
</P>
<P>
	Other residents ask where money they donated to Muhammad last  
year for youth programs has gone. And even Muhammad's former 
colleagues in the Nation of Islam, which offered support last year, 
have chosen to watch from the sidelines this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Muhammad, a former top aide to Nation of Islam leader Louis  
Farrakhan, was kicked out of the group partly due to his constant 
verbal attacks on Jews, Catholics, whites and others. He has taken 
to calling black elected officials who do not support him ``Uncle 
Toms'' and ``boot lickers'' for whites. 
</P>
<P>
	The increasing isolation of Muhammad and organizers of the march  
prompted a bizarre confrontation caught by television cameras 
earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaving a Harlem forum where Democratic presidential candidate  
Bill Bradley answered questions from the community, Perkins was 
jostled and called an ``Uncle Tom'' for not supporting the march. 
Someone told him: ``We should kill people like you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perkins has since been granted police protection.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
