<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Nearly Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar remained at a virtual standstill  
Friday as currency traders mulled statements by Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan in which he questioned the value of the 
stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0459, up  
from $1.0455 late Thursday. The dollar also was quoted at 111.56 
Japanese yen, up from 111.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, speaking Friday at a Kansas City Federal Reserve bank  
meeting in Jackson Hole, Wyo., said the extraordinary rise in stock 
prices the last five years has been mostly inexplicable, pushing 
the Dow lower for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	David Solin, a partner at Foreign Exchange Analytics in Essex,  
Conn., said the concern spilled over into the currency markets. The 
slight dip against the euro was likely caused traders selling 
dollars in fear of a potential stock selloff in the U.S., he said. 
The yen was essentially unaffected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It had to be the slowest day of the year,'' Solin said.  
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Monday is a bank holiday in London and many traders  
apparently took a long weekend, which contributed to Friday's quiet 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5310 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5331, and 1.4890 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5008. The British 
pound rose to $1.5878 from $1.5873. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8702 German 
marks, down from 1.8721; 6.2722 French francs, down from 6.2788; 
and 1,851 Italian lire, down from 1,854. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
