<DOCNO> APW19990827.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 18:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Ready To Re-Sign Armstrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Bulls keep looking for future help  
from their past. 
</P>
<P>
	First, they signed ex-center Will Perdue. Now they're on the  
verge doing the same with guard B.J. Armstrong, who played on the 
first three of six Bulls teams that won NBA titles in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong said he had reached a verbal agreement for a deal  
reported to be for one year at $1 million. The Bulls said Friday 
the contract had not been finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's partly physical stuff and some i's to dot and t's to  
cross,'' Bulls spokesman Tim Hallam said. ``We're looking at Monday 
or Tuesday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was the No. 18 pick in the 1989 draft out of Iowa. His  
best season was 1994, when he averaged 14.8 points and four assists 
per game. After the 1994-95 season he was left unprotected in the 
expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	He was picked by Toronto, which traded him to Golden State. He  
also played with Charlotte, was traded to Lakers and released and 
then signed by Orlando. Last year in 32 games, he averaged three 
points and two assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong's wife was born in Chicago, and he has continued to  
maintain a home in the suburbs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
