<HEADLINE> Reservation Attack Details Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PIERRE, S.D. (AP) -- The man that found a beating victim on the  
Pine Ridge Indian Reservation said there was no rope around his 
neck as the sheriff had said, though the victim's mother on Friday 
said she saw rope burns on her son's neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Details about the assault on Bradley Dean Young, 22, were  
unclear. Neither federal authorities nor Bennett County Sheriff 
Russel Waterbury returned calls Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Waterbury had earlier called the assault a hate crime, then said  
he didn't mean that it was racially motivated. Waterbury also said 
Young was found with a rope around his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Young was badly beaten but there was no rope around his neck  
when Marlin Fineran first found him in a field on the edge of the 
reservation, Fineran told The Rapid City Journal on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Young's mother, Carol Bucholz, told The Associated Press she saw  
rope burns on his neck when she saw him at Rapid City Regional 
Hospital, where Young remained in a coma on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were rope marks on his neck,'' she said Friday. She also  
said he had been dragged, but not by a vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Indians from the reservation have been charged with assault,  
and a juvenile has been arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and federal authorities have not filed any hate-crime  
charges, but said they're not ruling it out. 
  	   	
</P>
