<HEADLINE> Gatson Hurts Knee in Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Jason Gatson, a national title within  
his reach after coming close the last three years, tore a knee 
ligament while dismounting from the uneven bars Friday night and 
dropped out of the U.S. Gymnastics Championships while leading the 
all-around competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury could keep one of the United States' most promising  
male gymnasts out of the 2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson, 18, who finished second in 1996 and '98 and was third in  
the national championships in 1997, held a slim lead over training 
partner Blaine Wilson at the start of the all-around finals Friday. 
He built that lead in Wednesday's preliminary phase of the 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	He was injured on the first of Friday's six events. His right  
knee buckled as he flew off the uneven bars, and he fell to the 
side of the mat. After getting iced on the competition floor, he 
was helped to the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson's injury probably cleared the way for Wilson to claim an  
unprecedented fourth straight national all-around title. 
  	   	
</P>
