<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Airlines Chairman Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The China Airlines chairman, who was  
brought in to revamp the carrier's operations following a 1994 
crash in Japan, said Friday he offered to resign over this week's 
crash in Hong Kong that killed three people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taiwanese airline board didn't immediately accept, telling  
the chairman, Chiang Hung-I, it will hold off on any decision until 
crash investigations are finished. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have taken a lot of measures on flight safety in the past  
year, and we will look closely to see if there are still any 
defects or measures that have not been carried out thoroughly,'' 
Chiang told reporters after a board meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the three fatalities, more than 200 were injured  
when a CAL plane, flying from Bangkok to Hong Kong on Sunday, 
flipped upside down and burst into flames after the pilot brought 
the MD-11 jet down in a tropical storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Transport Minister Lin Fong-cheng said early this week he might  
ask the airline to replace its top executives following the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiang said some executives will be penalized after the  
directors decide who should be held responsible. Chiang told a 
newspaper CAL has made great efforts to improve its performance 
since he was put in charge after 264 people died in the crash in 
Nagoya, Japan, but ``apparently we have not done enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiang kept his job after a CAL crash in Taiwan last year killed  
all 196 people on board and six on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	The government, which holds a controlling stake in the Taiwanese  
air carrier, has demanded more reforms to safeguard flight safety. 
Lin has indicated he, too, might be punished, saying he wants the 
Cabinet of Premier Vincent Siew to decide on any penalties for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have yet to say what caused Sunday's crash. A  
Taiwanese aviation regulator has said the pilot was misled by his 
co-pilot about the severity of the cross winds as he tried to land 
during Tropical Storm Sam, which had shut down ferries, most buses 
and some roads and businesses in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	With help from Lufthansa German Airlines technicians, CAL  
reevaluated and retrained all of its 670 pilots, with a focus on 
making older ex-military pilots better team players. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the United Daily News, Chiang said  
Lufthansa technicians have also helped modify and upgrade CAL's 
maintenance plants and ground operations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
