<HEADLINE> Injury Subdues Jordan Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Brian Jordan's first trip to St. Louis as a  
visiting player started out more low key than he had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, who left the Cardinals after six seasons to sign a $40  
million, five-year contract with Atlanta, sat out the series opener 
Friday night because of a sore right wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	He also expects to miss Saturday's game but hopes to play in the  
finale on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said he had no hard feelings for the Cardinals, who made  
no effort to re-sign him, citing his injury history. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all behind me,'' said Jordan, hitting .295 with 22  
homers and 100 RBIs. ``I've moved on and I've matured as a player. 
I never burn bridges. Maybe I'll be back here later in my career, 
so I wish them well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several hours before the game, Jordan visited with several  
Cardinals players just outside the St. Louis clubhouse. Manager 
Tony La Russa also came out to shake his hand and ask with fingers 
obviously crossed: ``Gonna miss all three games?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said he missed the St. Louis fans.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Atlanta fans are great, but not as good as here,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan had three cortisone shots earlier this week for the  
injury, caused when he was hit by a pitch. He fears the bone is 
chipped. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's an unfortunate thing, but I'll just try to play through  
it,'' Jordan said. ``I've got to get it right for September because 
these are important games.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
