<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Aims for Bahamas, U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Forecasters expect a weather system  
moving east across the United States to force Hurricane Dennis away 
from Florida, but the Bahamas might not be so lucky. The National 
Hurricane Center in Miami said Dennis might never hit land, but 
that it also could turn and strike near South Carolina as early as 
Sunday, when it could be packing winds up to 109 mph, said 
forecaster Robert Molleda. Dennis is about 150 miles east of the 
Bahamas now, stirring up winds and rain that knocked furniture into 
swimming pools and left people fearful for fragile trees and plant 
life that had just begun to recover from Hurricane Andrew in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic: US Helps 'Murderers'  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Taking advantage of pervasive  
anti-Serb violence in Kosovo, President Slobodan Milosevic is 
sounding an anti-American campaign he hopes will help him stay in 
power. In a statement following a meeting yesterday of top Yugoslav 
leaders, Milosevic said the United States was in ``alliance with 
murderers, drug traffickers and terrorists of the Kosovo Liberation 
Army.'' The statement suggested that opposition leaders demanding 
Milosevic's resignation were linked to the alleged American 
campaign against Kosovo's Serbs. 

</P>
<P>
	Western Fires Roaring in Six States  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- More than two dozen major fires are  
burning across the West, charring thousands of acres and forcing 
the California governor to call out the National Guard to help. 
Experts feared that firefighting resources were being stretched 
thin. ``The situation is escalating and it's getting to the point 
where we're concerned about being able to respond to all the fires 
adequately,'' said Janelle Smith of the National Interagency Fire 
Center in Boise, Idaho. By early today, 27 fires have burned 
121,000 acres of grass, brush and timber in six states: California, 
Nevada, Oregon, Montana, Washington and Idaho. 

</P>
<P>
	Violence in Turkey's Ruins  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Tension and fear over the instability of  
buildings left standing after Turkey's massive earthquake are 
mounting, with an argument between two families over whether or not 
to tear down a structure leading to a shootout that left two people 
dead. The Anatolia news agency reported yesterday that the two 
families were arguing about whether a quake-damaged building that 
was leaning on another should be ripped down. Further details 
weren't immediately available. Construction and safety issues were 
in the spotlight today, with the Daily News, a nationally 
circulated Turkish newspaper, reporting that three-quarters of 
Istanbul's buildings, most of them in shantytowns ringing the city, 
are unlicensed and illegal. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright To Gauge Middle East Peace  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With an agreement on an Israeli pullback  
falling into place, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is 
exploring further Mideast peacemaking with senior Palestinian 
officials. Albright is due to travel to the region next week where 
she would witness the signing of an agreement between Israel and 
the Palestinian Authority if final details can be worked out. The 
agreement now taking shape calls for Israel to resume a pullback 
from 13 percent of the West Bank that was promised last October but 
halted after 2 percent was surrendered. Israel would relinquish 7 
percent this October and the remaining 4 percent in January. 

</P>
<P>
	19 Chinese Dead in Mine Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- An explosion in a coal mine in central China  
earlier this week killed 19 people and left 36 missing and feared 
dead, a newspaper report said today. The gas explosion occurred 
Tuesday during a power outage at a state-owned mine in Hanzhuang 
village near the city of Pingdingshan in Henan province, the 
Workers Daily reported. A large fire hampered rescue efforts, and 
only 19 of the 74 miners who had been working in the mine were 
known to have survived, it said. The cause of the explosion was 
under investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Says New Telescope Works Well  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Chandra X-ray Observatory, NASA's new $1  
billion X-ray telescope, is performing as expected. Scientists say 
it transmitted crystal clear images of an exploding star. ``We were 
astounded by these images,'' Harvey Tananbaum, director of the 
Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory's Chandra X-ray Center in 
Cambridge, Mass., said Thursday in a statement. The orbiting 
telescope captured as its first view an image of the Cassiopeia A 
supernova, a star in the Milky Way galaxy that exploded about 300 
years ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks End Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei closed at 17,599.37 points, down 66.92  
points Friday. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 
127.59 points to 11,198.45 at Thursday's close after setting a new 
record high Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Johnson: 'I Can Run Faster'  
</P>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Michael Johnson has the record he craved  
his entire career; now he wants to break it again. Just minutes 
after shattering the 11-year-old world record in the 400 meters 
with an electrifying time of 43.18 seconds, Johnson set his sights 
on running even faster. ``I can do better,'' said Johnson, after 
winning his fourth consecutive 400 title at the World 
Championships. ``I know I can run 42 seconds.'' Johnson shaved .11 
seconds off the record of 43.29 set by fellow American Butch 
Reynolds in 1988, the longest standing men's track record. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
