<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mori Wins Gold in 400 Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Fabrizio Mori of Italy, who had initially  
been disqualified in the semifinals, won a controversial 400-meter 
hurdles in the World Championships on Friday, defeating defending 
champion Stephane Diagana of France. Switzerland's Marcel Schelbert 
took the bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	France appealed Mori's victory, arguing he had stepped outside  
his lane on the final curve. The appeal was rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mori is confirmed as the winner,'' IAAF spokesman Giorgio  
Reineri said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the semifinal, Mori had been disqualified at first for  
running outside his lane but Italy won an appeal, allowing Mori to 
stage his strong comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's final, Mori stormed past Diagana over the last 30  
meters and finished in an Italian-record 47.72 seconds, the best 
time of the season. Diagana, who stumbled at the last gate, was .40 
seconds behind. Schelbert crossed the line in 48.13. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I reached the final bend, I felt my legs going faster and  
faster and so even though Diagana and the Pole (Pawel Januszewski) 
were ahead of me, I knew I would catch them and win,'' Mori said. 
</P>
<P>
	Diagana's chances went at the last hurdle, which he clipped.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so disappointed. I was good until the 10th hurdle, where I  
made a small error. I dragged my foot and it cost me first place 
because Mori was coming back so fast,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The final was hurt by a lot of withdrawals. Pre-championship  
favorite Llewellyn Herbert of South Africa, who had set the 
season's best performance, withdrew on Monday with a left 
quadriceps injury. 
</P>
<P>
	To throw the race even more open, Britain's Chris Rawlinson, who  
owned the season's third-best mark, also had to bow out Monday, 
injuring his ankle in training. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelo Taylor of the United States and Zambia's Samuel Matete,  
two more medal hopefuls, failed to make it to the final. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
