<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane A Distant Threat in S.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) -- Lisa and Enio DiNardo drove more than  
15 hours from Canada to have fun along the seaside, and on Friday 
they were not going to let the threat of Hurricane Dennis spoil it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to make the best of it,'' said Mrs. DiNardo of  
Stoney Creek, Ontario. ``As long as it's not snow, we're happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dennis was still more than 300 miles away, churning  
through the Atlantic near the Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	People kept their eyes on the weather reports. But with  
forecasts that the storm, if it came ashore here, would not land 
until at least Monday, most people in this tourist city enjoyed the 
sun and surf. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know about the hurricane until we got here,''  
DiNardo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lifeguard Mike Miehm watched as hundreds of people sat under  
brightly colored umbrellas, jumped in the rolling waves and flew 
kites in the gentle breeze on a steamy afternoon. A hurricane was 
not in their plans, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not really a huge issue right now,'' Miehm said. ``It's a  
lot of work because people try to get as much surfing before the 
hurricane. It's really dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly every hotel sign said there were vacancies, but that is  
normal for this time of year, said Ashby Ward, president of the 
Chamber of Commerce. He estimated there were about 250,000 people 
in town -- a thinner crowd as the summer winds down and children 
have started school. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wait and see right now,'' Ward said. ``There doesn't seem  
to be a panic yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Breakers Hotel, manager Kay Harris said most of 400 rooms  
were filled for Friday night with golfers, tourists and some 
reporters, but the media hype chased the walk-in business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally we have a trail of traffic up Highway 501 and tonight  
there's nothing,'' Ms. Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the weather channels and the Internet, ``it seems we start  
earlier with the worry and warnings,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
