<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 13:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Scores Second World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The ``Star-Spangled Banner'' had just  
stopped playing at the Pan Pacific swimming championships 
presentation ceremony when Lenny Krayzelburg began gently clapping. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian-turned-American was saluting his new country and the  
support of the fans who had just cheered him to his second world 
record in three days. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an amazing feeling, one that I'll always remember,''  
Krayzelburg said Friday after smashing the 200-meter backstroke 
record. His time of 1 minute, 55.87 seconds was 7-10ths of a second 
faster than the 1:56.57 set by Spain's Martin Lopez Zubero at 
Tuscaloosa, Ala.on Nov. 23, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Krayzelburg broke the 100-meter world record.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking forward to this meet for about a year, and I had  
a good feeling about it,'' Krayzelburg said. ``I guess I went out 
kind of quick tonight, but the crowd really spurred me home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krayzelburg, who became an American citizen in 1995, six years  
after he and his family emigrated from the former Soviet Union, 
said his most important goal remains next year's Sydney Olympics, 
where the swimming competition will be held in the same pool. 
</P>
<P>
	``My time won't matter -- as long as I can get the gold in both  
the 100 and 200,'' Krayzelburg said. But rather than become 
complacent, the 23-year-old Californian plans to use it as extra 
training fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything, there will be more motivation because a lot of  
people will be out to try to beat me next year,'' said Krayzelburg. 
``It's an Olympics, so you never know what's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Schubert was Krayzelburg's former coach and is now the  
United States national team coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just worked so hard, he's always there, two hours in the  
morning, three hours in the afternoon,'' Schubert said. ``He never 
misses a session.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krayzelburg, who will have a chance to add a third gold medal  
when he swims for the U.S medley relay team Sunday, didn't miss a 
chance to show his pleasure with Friday's record swim. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Krayzelburg said, some of his friends criticized him  
for not appearing pleased with his world championship wins because 
he wasn't pleased with his time. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments after Friday's success, Krayzelburg pointed brazenly to  
the scoreboard with his world record time flashing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't going to be accused of that again,'' Krayzelburg  
said. ``I had been thinking of a way to show my happiness, and I 
figured that would do it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 14:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bulls Hire Ex-San Jose State Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- San Jose State coach Phil Johnson was  
hired by the Chicago Bulls on Friday as an assistant to head coach 
Tim Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 42, joins the Bulls after only one season at San Jose  
State. He led the Spartans to a 12-16 record, a nine-game 
improvement over the previous season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel fortunate, in that Phil is an outstanding young  
coaching commodity with an excellent amount of high-level 
experience,'' said Bulls general manager Jerry Krause. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was an assistant under Floyd at the University of New  
Orleans from 1991-1993 and spent five seasons as an assistant coach 
at Arizona before going to San Jose State. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he was excited to be joining the Bulls, ``who are,  
in my mind, the premier professional sports organization in the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls lost assistant coaches Tex Winter and Frank Hamblen  
over the summer. Both resigned to join former Bulls coach Phil 
Jackson with the Los Angeles Lakers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
