<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Accused of IBM Bomb Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An 18-year-old Panamanian admitted he sent  
e-mail bomb threats to IBM, claiming he would demolish the company 
headquarters unless he was paid $5 million, authorities said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jahair Joel Navarro was charged with threatening to use a weapon  
of mass destruction. The crime, which falls under federal 
anti-terrorism statutes, carries a maximum sentence of life in 
prison without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Navarro, a legal resident of the United States, was ordered held  
without bail after prosecutors told a judge he had sent a similar 
threat to Microsoft Corp. in Redmond, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	A complaint signed by FBI agent Robert Antonez said Navarro,  
during a search of his home Thursday, admitted sending the threats 
to both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Navarro allegedly identified himself as ``Shadowmega'' in an  
e-mail sent Tuesday to IBM Chief Executive Officer Lou Gerstner. 
</P>
<P>
	The message said five bombs would destroy the company's  
headquarters in Armonk if he was not paid $5 million by Friday, 
according to U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and police traced the e-mail to an America Online  
account owned by Navarro's stepfather. He could not be reached for 
comment Friday. A message was left at the family's home. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents who searched the family's apartment in Brooklyn found  
bomb-making recipes and documents relating to terrorist techniques 
that appeared to have been downloaded from the Internet, White 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI spokesman Joseph Valiquette said no bombs were ever found.  
</P>
<P>
	An IBM spokesman had no comment except to say the company was  
cooperating with authorities. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
