<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Marine Dies at Age 107 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TENAFLY, N.J. (AP) -- Joseph Gold, the nation's oldest living  
Marine and one of the few remaining World War I veterans, has died. 
He was 107. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold died Wednesday of pneumonia at a Tenafly nursing home, his  
son said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold, who served with the American Expeditionary Force in the  
Battle of Belleau Wood in June, 1918, was one of two servicemen to 
receive France's Legion of Honor award last month. 
</P>
<P>
	At his request, Gold was buried Friday to the trumpeting of taps  
and a Marine honor guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very proud of Joe Gold,'' said Frank Hall, commandant  
of the Gooney Bird detachment of the U.S. Marine Corps League and a 
veteran of World War II. ``He gave us an insight into what the guys 
did before us.'' The Gooney Birds are a local chapter of retired 
Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few weeks ago, interviewers from the U.S. Marine Corps  
Research Center arrived at Gold's nursing home to record his 
thoughts on the war he fought and his service in the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to record him for Marine Corps history, so that  
Marines 100 years from now can listen to him and understand what 
it's like,'' said senior archivist Michael Miller. ``I asked him 
what it was like to be one of the oldest living Marines, and he 
said it made him really proud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the interview finished, he sang the Marine Corps hymn  
three-quarters through, lapsing into humming only at the end, 
Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he sang the Marine Corps hymn, there wasn't hardly a dry  
eye in the place,'' Miller said. ``And his grip was just a Marine 
grip. He grabbed my hand so hard it hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gold was the oldest living Marine and one of only a few who  
remembered fighting during World War I, according to Marine 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	Stabbed in the hand by a German bayonet, Gold nonetheless stayed  
with the Marines in Europe. He remained until 1919 to help with 
postwar reconstruction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
