<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Krayzelburg, Heyns Break Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- American Lenny Krayzelburg set his  
second world record while South African Penny Heyns continued her 
amazing feats at the Pan Pacific swimming championships today. 
</P>
<P>
	Krayzelburg broke an 8-year-old record in the 200 backstroke to  
add to his 100 record from Wednesday, while Heyns broke her seventh 
world record in her last 10 races during the 200 breaststroke 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one record has fallen on all six days of the meet so  
far -- 10 overall -- in the pool which will be used at next year's 
Olympic Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The perfect record could be extended to seven days with a meet  
official saying the sport's governing body FINA has given Heyns 
permission to attempt to break her own 50 world record in a special 
time trial following Saturday's heats. 
</P>
<P>
	American Jenny Thompson, who broke a 100 butterfly record,  
claimed her fourth gold when she won the 100 freestyle final. 
Thompson finished in 54.89 to finish well ahead of Sarah Ryan of 
Australia at 55.58, adding her second individual gold to two relay 
victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Wilkens of the United States won the last final today,  
taking the 200 medley in 2:01.01. 
</P>
<P>
	Krayzelburg had a time of 1:55.87 in the final, beating the  
1:56.57 set by Martin Lopez Zubero of Spain in November 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I was close the last couple of months so I was very  
confident coming into this meet. But I felt a bit of pressure and 
I'm so relieved now. It's awesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns revealed before the race that she was using the  
controversial food supplement Creatine, billed as a legal 
alternative to anabolic steroids. 
</P>
<P>
	While she believes her times might have plunged without the  
supplement, Heyns has been on a remarkable roll for the past five 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	She started the spurt at last month's Janet Evans Invitational  
in Los Angeles when she broke the 100 and 200 mark twice each. She 
broke the 100 in the heats of the this meet and missed it in the 
semis and final while easily winning gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns took the 200 record down to 2:42.42 in Thursday's semis  
and lowered it significantly in today's final to 2:23.64. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am shocked by that,'' said Heyns. ``As much as I tried to  
convince myself that I was relaxed tonight, I felt a little 
distracted during the race. Coming home it wasn't as easy as it has 
been. Now I know why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns said she went out faster than she planned.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a weird race, I didn't feel as much in control as I  
have the other days,'' Heyns said. ``I'm blown away, I'm just 
having a lot of fun. The records are a bonus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns has returned from contemplating retirement after the  
Atlanta Olympics, where she won the breaststroke double. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she got to the stage of hating her sport, but after  
deciding to carry on to next year's Sydney Olympics she wanted to 
do everything possible to make sure she competed at her best, 
including taking the legal supplement Creatine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be swimming pretty well whether I was on it or not,''  
Heyns said. ``But I have the attitude that I don't want to get on 
the blocks during my career and know that I've trained and swum as 
hard as I could but that there was a nutritional side that I didn't 
do the best I could in. I want to cover all the bases.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
