<HEADLINE> Mademoiselle Editor Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Elizabeth Crow is stepping down after six years  
as editor of Mademoiselle, a Conde Nast magazine targeted at young 
women. 
</P>
<P>
	Conde Nast has not yet named a replacement for Crow, who agreed  
to stay on until December. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was announced late Thursday by Conde Nast's editorial  
director, James Truman. Conde Nast is owned by Advance Publications 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Crow had previously served in senior editorial positions at  
Parents magazine and New York magazine. She also headed Gruner and 
Jahr, the U.S. magazine unit of the German media conglomerate 
Bertelsmann that publishes Family Circle and McCalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Conde Nast, which also publishes The New Yorker, Vanity Fair, GQ  
and Wired, announced Tuesday it is buying Fairchild Publications 
from Walt Disney Co. Fairchild publishes Women's Wear Daily, W and 
Jane. 



  	   	
