<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall After Greenspan Remarks / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today after Federal Reserve Chairman  
Alan Greenspan, in remarks at a banking conference, did not discuss 
the central bank's interest rate policy. 
</P>
<P>
	At midday, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 47.18 to  
11,151.27. The Dow fell 127 points on Thursday amid profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also were lower today. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 7.86 at 1,354.15, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 13.84 at 2,760.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, speaking today at a Kansas City Federal Reserve bank  
meeting, talked about the stock market, saying the extraordinary 
rise in stock prices the last five years has been mostly 
inexplicable. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors seemed disappointed that Greenspan did not confirm  
many beliefs that Tuesday's 0.25 percent interest hike will be 
enough to quell inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The presumption is he thinks the stock market is too high and  
is contributing to overheating the economy which could cause 
inflation,'' said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital 
Markets Group in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed hinted Tuesday that no additional rate increases might  
be needed this year unless the economy showed signs of overheating 
or if inflation flared up. 
</P>
<P>
	A Commerce Department report today indicated the economy is  
growing moderately. Personal spending rose 0.4 percent in July, 
below what analysts had expected. Personal income rose a 
slower-than-expected 0.2 percent last month. The gain, the smallest 
this year, followed a strong 0.7 percent increase in June. 
</P>
<P>
	American Express, down 2 3/16 at 145, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson,  
down 1 5/8 at 102 13/16 were the the biggest losers in the Dow. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mixed on the Nasdaq, as Intel rose 1 9/16  
at 82 5/8 and Microsoft dropped 1 7/8 to 92 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 258.3 million shares, 
down significantly from Thursday's session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index was down 2.54 at 433.48.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
