<HEADLINE> Soybean Futures Push Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Forecasts for dry weather through most of the  
soybean belt next week helped push soybean futures higher Friday on 
the Chicago Board of Trade. Grain futures were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were buoyed by continued market talk that China is  
in the market for U.S. soybean products and may have bought between 
250,000 tons and 350,000 tons of soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures edged down to a four-week low for December amid  
pressure from the impending harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures slipped, pressured by a lack of export sales that  
would help reduce relatively large inventories. With Canada's 
competing crop expected to be larger than originally forecast, 
investors are concerned 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 4 cents to $2.79 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.15 1/4 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.14 a bushel; November soybeans rose 4 1/4 cents to 
$4.71 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures prices were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .20 cent to 66.55 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .25 cent to 78.92 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell .18 cent to 44.97 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies rose 1.25 cents to 58.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
