<HEADLINE> Individual Schools Decide Badge Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- The district that includes Columbine High  
School says its individual schools may decide for themselves 
whether to have students wear identification badges as a security 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jefferson County School Board this month informally approved  
a plan to require staff and students in all secondary schools to 
wear badges. But students complained and administrators questioned 
the idea's practicality. 
</P>
<P>
	The five board members said Thursday they had reconsidered. A  
formal vote on the proposal is expected next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are concerned about their children's privacy. They  
don't see what difference it will make,'' said board member Tori 
Merritts. ``They're concerned about punitive measures to enforce 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The badges were one of several recommendations made by a safety  
task force formed after the April 20 shooting rampage at Columbine. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the plan said tags would have been ineffective in  
preventing that attack because the gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan 
Klebold, were students and would have had badges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
