<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprinter Johnson Nearly Gave Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- A few weeks ago, Michael Johnson was ready  
to write off the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobbled by another injury and stung by accusations that he was  
ducking a showdown against Maurice Greene, the American sprint star 
was at one of the lowest points of his brilliant career. 
</P>
<P>
	But Johnson sat down with his coach, Clyde Hart, and agreed to  
continue chasing the goal he'd set at the start of the year: 
breaking the world 400-meter record in the final of the World 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hart-to-heart talk paid off Thursday night when the double  
Olympic champion ran an electrifying 43.18 seconds to win his 
fourth consecutive world title and slash .11 off Butch Reynolds' 
11-year-old mark, the longest standing record in a men's track 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's indescribable,'' Johnson said Friday after celebrating  
late into the night with friends and family. ``When you've been 
chasing the record for so long, it's relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it couldn't have come at a better time in my career.  
After all the injuries I've had this year, having to pull out of a 
few meets, this was especially gratifying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was asked to compare the 400 record with the 200 mark of  
19.32 seconds he set at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're like children,'' the 31-year-old Texan said. ``They're  
both valuable, very dear to me, special for their own particular 
reason. The 200 was the first one. This one is more special, not 
just because of the world record, but because of the time, and that 
I broke it at this stage in my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's status for the championships had been in serious doubt  
after he pulled up with a strained hamstring in a 400 race in 
Stockholm, Sweden, on July 30. He went home to Waco, Texas, feeling 
physically and emotionally spent. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was about to throw it in for the season,'' Hart said  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had definitely lost the passion for the sport for a  
while,'' said his agent, Brad Hunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was upset that people had questioned his withdrawals  
from meets with injuries and accused him of avoiding a 200-meter 
race against Greene at the U.S. nationals in June in Eugene, Ore. 
Johnson pulled out of the meet citing a recurrence of the hip 
alignment problem that has plagued him throughout his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael was just disappointed,'' Hart said. ``You're injured  
and people say you are ducking somebody. He couldn't understand why 
people thought he wasn't telling the truth. That hurt him. 
</P>
<P>
	``But eventually everything turned around. We used it as a  
motivating factor -- to prove himself on the track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart put Johnson through two weeks of grueling workouts  
involving 350-meter runs. Johnson skipped the prestigious 
Weltklasse meet in Zurich, Switzerland, to train at home. When he 
came to Seville, he was in perfect shape for the record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew and he knew the record was within him,'' Hart said.  
``We didn't need the races to tell us. The workouts told us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the record fell Thursday night, the surprise was not that  
Johnson had broken it, but by how much. 
</P>
<P>
	What's so impressive about the record is that Johnson has had no  
real rivals in the 400 to push him. He won Thursday's race by a 
huge margin, with silver medalist Sanderlei Parrela of Brazil 
finishing more than a second behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realized way back that I would have to (go for the record)  
by myself,'' Johnson said. ``All the time I've been chasing this 
record, I knew I would have to do it alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said his next goal is to break the 43-second barrier --  
ideally at next year's Sydney Olympics, where he'll be attempting 
another 200-400 double and running in the 1,600-meter relay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always felt I can go under 43,'' he said. ``Running 43.18  
is just confirmation of that. In Sydney, I think there'll be the 
opportunity to run under 43.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, don't look for any sprint match race between  
Johnson and Greene, the 100-meter champion and world record-holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson still has bad memories of his 150-meter match race in  
1997 against Canada's Donovan Bailey, the 1996 Olympic 100-meter 
champion. Johnson pulled up with torn quadriceps, an injury from 
which Hart said he has still not fully recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to get involved in any special matchups any  
more,'' Johnson said. ``I don't think there would be anything for 
me to gain by doing that. I think those matchups should be left to 
the Olympic trials and Olympic Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Johnson, who is scheduled to run in the 200 at next week's  
Golden League meet in Brussels, Belgium, said he would be happy to 
face Green there. After Brussels, Johnson plans to run in only one 
more meet this year, in Rieti, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	First, though, Johnson will run anchor on the U.S. 1,600-meter  
relay team in Sunday's final event of the championships. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory would give Johnson a career total of nine gold medals  
at the championships. He's currently tied with Carl Lewis for the 
all-time record with eight golds -- four in the 400, two in the 200 
and two in the relay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
