<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 19:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Pessimistic About Boeing Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Boeing Co. chairman Phil Condit said Friday  
the company faces ``reasonably good'' odds of avoiding a strike by 
its largest union despite pessimism from machinist union officials 
that a deal can be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's final contract proposal was expected to be delivered  
late Friday night to International Association of Machinists and 
Aerospace Workers, which represents 44,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	A firm proposal was delivered earlier to the union earlier in  
the day, but union spokesman Tim Flynn said it was not the final 
offer. ``A cursory look at it suggests there's quite a distance to 
go, but we'll see what happens,'' Flynn said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit told reporters late Friday afternoon that cost was the  
bottom line for Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company. He 
emphasized the company's struggle to compete with European rival 
Airbus Industrie. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past it was the performance of your product that made  
the difference,'' Condit said at the hotel where negotiations are 
taking place. ``Airbus is a capable competitor. So the battles are 
about price ... that's the environment we're dealing in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Condit declined to discuss how the company is preparing for a  
strike, but said the Seattle-based company is in ``good financial 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've reached good, solid labor agreements with a lot of our  
bargaining units,'' Condit said. ``We've got big pieces of our 
company that will be running and stable'' even if the Machinists 
vote to strike on Sept. 1, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said that a strike would shut down  
some factories. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides acknowledge a lack of consensus on major issues: job  
security, health care, pensions and keeping a traditional work 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each one of those is a walk issue. All bets are off if they're  
not addressed,'' said Mark Blondin, a full-time union 
representative at Boeing's Everett, Wash., plant. ``I really firmly 
believe they'll walk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union is seeking to preserve jobs, improve medical benefits  
and increase pensions. The company wants to cut costs through 
subcontracting, paying less for health benefits and adopting a 
flexible work week. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks come as Boeing is undertaking a massive job cut  
program. From a high of 238,000 in June 1998, Boeing plans to 
reduce its work force to between 185,000 and 195,000 by the end of 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The average machinist at Boeing earns $40,000 a year, not  
counting benefits or overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The current 44-month contract covers 31,000 workers in  
Washington state, 1,400 in Portland, Ore., and 11,600 in Wichita, 
Kan. Boeing employs about 210,000 worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members are expected to vote Wednesday on whether to  
accept or reject the offer as well as whether to authorize a 
strike. The current contract expires at midnight Wednesday, and a 
strike could begin immediately if two-thirds of the Machinists vote 
to authorize it. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the Machinists in Seattle, Portland, Ore., and Wichita,  
Kan., voted informally to support a strike if negotiations failed. 
They have gone on strike in two of the past three contract talks, 
most recently for 69 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members said Friday they were ready for a strike, no  
matter how long it takes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Roberts, a material processor and shop steward at Boeing's  
Renton, Wash., plant, said he had enough money set aside so he 
wouldn't start to feel a pinch from the strike for at least four 
months. Most of his co-workers were similarly well situated, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts also said he expected well over the required two-thirds  
of union members to authorize a strike and cited last month's vote, 
in which 98 percent of the 19,000 Machinists from those three 
cities said they would support a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the numbers going to fall short of that,'' he  
said. ``After all, you have people here who have 10 or 15 years 
here and they've gone through and bled for the younger workers to 
have these benefits when they get hired in. When Boeing goes to 
take away those benefits, it's a slap in the face for those workers 
who've been here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts, who has worked at Boeing for nearly two years, and  
Cliff Standfill, a a tool maker at Renton who has worked for Boeing 
for 20 years, agreed that job security was the most important issue 
for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a money issue, it never has been,'' Standfill said.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
