<DOCNO> APW19990827.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 09:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton golfed with Prince  
Andrew today and jokingly bet the island of Martha's Vineyard on 
the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and the Duke of York teed off at Farm Neck Golf Club  
where the president, with the prince as a passenger, stopped his 
golf cart in front of a gaggle of reporters and photographers and 
introduced his royal guest. 
</P>
<P>
	The dukes of York, he asserted, were hereditary owners of  
Martha's Vineyard, located in the Atlantic off the Massachusetts 
coast, in the 17th century. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what the bet is? If he beats me we have to give him  
back the island,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you want the island back, sir,'' a reporter shouted.  
</P>
<P>
	Andrew smiled.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you when I've won,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The prince was heard to say that the play would be without a  
handicap, ``flat, no strokes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the foursome were Sir Evelyn Rothschild of London  
and a man preliminarily identified by the White House as Tony 
Fisher of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The golf outing came after Clinton ended two days of seclusion  
at his borrowed summer house with a burst of vacation activity on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He went horseback riding. Then he played golf, twice, 34 holes  
in all. Then he threw on a sweater and, accompanied by first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton and their daughter Chelsea, joined friends 
at a clambake on the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The clambake at the home of Mattel executive Bill Rollnick and  
his wife, Nancy Ellison, is an annual event. The Clintons were 
there two years ago when an aide told them Princess Diana had been 
killed in an automobile crash in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The clambake provided a quiet conclusion to what otherwise was a  
busy day for Clinton. In a stark turnaround from the seclusion he'd 
been in for the two previous days, the president arose early and 
headed to the Blue Heron Farm for a morning of horseback riding. 
</P>
<P>
	A squadron of wild geese flew over a nearby field as Clinton and  
Chelsea rode on sandy narrow paths through groves of oak trees at 
the 40-acre farm. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton left after an hour and spent the rest of the day at the  
Farm Neck Golf Club playing golf with two sets of college friends. 
During the first round with Warren Spector, Tom Flexner and Ken 
Iscol -- all of New York City -- Clinton sent his first shot into the 
woods, a well-traveled territory for Clinton golf balls. 
</P>
<P>
	During a later round with Clare O'Callahan, Maurie Flanagan and  
her son, Sean, Clinton paused after his first shot and asked: ``Is 
it OK?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Hit one more. Go ahead,'' replied Sean. So Clinton did.  
</P>
<P>
	``Much better,'' O'Callahan offered.  
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons are scheduled to leave Martha's Vineyard off the  
Massachusetts coast on Saturday for a round of fund-raisers in the 
posh Hamptons district of eastern Long Island. Beneficiaries will 
include the Democratic National Committee and Mrs. Clinton's 
expected campaign to win an open U.S. Senate seat in New York 
state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 11:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton golfed with royalty  
Friday and jokingly staked the island of Martha's Vineyard on the 
outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	The president joined Britain's Prince Andrew, the duke of York,  
on the links at the Farm Neck Golf Club. He noted that in the 17th 
century the ground on which they stood -- indeed all of this island 
off the Massachusetts coast -- was owned by the dukes of York. 
</P>
<P>
	Prince Andrew has held the title since his mother, Queen  
Elizabeth, conferred it in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what the bet is? If he beats me, we have to give him  
back the island,'' Clinton said, stopping his golf cart near a 
gaggle of reporters and photographers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you want the island back, sir,'' a reporter shouted.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you when I've won,'' said the grinning prince, a  
passenger in the president's electric cart. 
</P>
<P>
	If the question of the ownership of Martha's Vineyard hadn't  
been settled by the American Revolution, its 14,000 permanent 
residents and the scores of thousands of vacationers who visit each 
autumn might have had reason for worry: 
</P>
<P>
	The prince's first shot sailed down the middle of the fairway;  
the president's veered radically off course. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't go way over there,'' he implored.  
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, with the ball still in the air, there was a loud  
crash. A staff member in the nearby clubhouse had dropped a tub of 
dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton usually gives himself the luxury of a mulligan or two  
when he tees off, taking advantage of the extra shots that some 
golfers grant their partners. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the prince made do with his initial shot, Clinton  
followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was evidently played without handicap.  
</P>
<P>
	``No strokes. ... All flat,'' Prince Andrew decreed.  
</P>
<P>
	The royal golf match was the highlight of Clinton's last full  
vacation day on Martha's Vineyard, the seventh time he has spent 
summer weeks here during his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	The vacation's second half will be at the Finger Lakes region of  
upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton are set to  
leave Saturday for the posh Hamptons region of Long Island for a 
series of fund-raisers intended to raise money for Democratic 
campaigns in general and for Mrs. Clinton's likely New York Senate 
campaign in particular. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night at East Hampton the Clintons are hosts at the  
airport terminal to a buffet reception of the young Democrats' 
``Saxophone Club.'' At $250 per person, some 800 people are 
expected to turn out for the Clintons and comedian Jon Stewart to 
net about $200,000 for the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, it's on to a $1,000 per plate barbecue dinner at a  
private East Hampton residence. Singer Phoebe Snow will entertain 
the 300 people contributing jointly to the DNC, Mrs. Clinton's 
anticipated Senate race and the Democratic Senatorial Campaign 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the Clintons star at a $5,000 per person lunch for 80  
at a South Hampton home. The first $1,000 of every ticket price, a 
party official said, will go to Mrs. Clinton's race with the 
remainder being shared by the DNC and DSCC. 
</P>
<P>
	In the priciest of the galas, rocker Jon Bon Jovi provides the  
music at a Bridgehampton dinner on Sunday night solely benefiting 
the DNC. At $25,000 per couple, the event is expected to bag 
$900,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skippy Trademark in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A woman who claims the trademark for a  
Depression-era cartoon character created by her late father was 
pirated by the makers of Skippy peanut butter agreed Friday to 
remove her accusations from a Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Joan Crosby Tibbetts, 66, of Annandale, told a  
federal judge that she would temporarily remove passages from her 
Internet site that claim Bestfoods, a company that was spun off by 
CPC International, stole the trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies claim they are being harmed by her ``false and  
malicious'' statements. Ms. Tibbetts declined to discuss her case 
Friday on the advice of her lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	The case, which has been in and out of courts for years, had its  
roots during the Depression, when Percy Crosby's cartoon strip 
Skippy was a favorite in newspapers. The character spawned a radio 
show and the Academy award-winning movie ``Skippy,'' which stared 
Jackie Cooper, then a child actor. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers paid Crosby for rights to license products with  
the Skippy name, and Crosby got rich. 
</P>
<P>
	Crosby, however, apparently never cut a deal with Rosefield  
Packing Co. when it began marketing a new type of peanut butter. In 
1933, Crosby fought the company's effort to register the Skippy 
name with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, but, according to 
The Washington Post, there is no record he ever filed suit to 
defend the trademark, which expired in 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, his life had begun to crumble. His marriage broke up,  
King Features dropped his cartoon and he was accused of evading 
taxes. He attempted suicide, was classified as paranoid 
schizophrenic and was committed to a mental ward where he spent his 
dying days. 
</P>
<P>
	Skippy, however, had again become a household name, this time  
because of peanut butter. In 1968, Ms. Tibbetts became 
administrator of her father's estate and sought compensation from 
CPC International, a successor to Rosefield that later spun off 
Bestfoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tibbetts accepted a $25,000 check, but later alleged she was  
duped, according to the Post. 
</P>
<P>
	She sued in 1980, but a judge ruled that her trademark rights  
had elapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1986, CPC International sued Ms. Tibbetts, claiming she had  
infringed on the company's trademark by attempting to sell products 
through her company, Skippy Inc. U.S. District Judge Richard 
Williams ordered her to stop claiming the trademark rights had been 
stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the case was once again before Williams. He gave Ms.  
Tibbetts five days to remove certain statements from her Web site. 
Another hearing was set for Sept. 17. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 08:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Esquire Allowed in Fla. Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Prisoners in Florida will be allowed to  
read about a California guard ``who did some very bad things'' to 
inmates despite concern that the Esquire magazine article is 
``dangerously inflammatory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member Department of Corrections panel decided late  
Thursday that prisoners should have access to the magazine, which 
tells the story of Roscoe ``Bonecrusher'' Pondexter, a guard at 
Corcoran State Prison in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The September issue appears at the same time Florida prisons are  
dealing with the recent death of an inmate and an investigation 
into whether guards killed him. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine describes ``how a nice guy, Roscoe Pondexter,  
became a brutal guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the North Florida Reception Center prison in Lake  
Butler intercepted an inmate's copy of the magazine after reading 
``The Making of Bonecrusher'' by Richard Stratton. 
</P>
<P>
	They passed the story to the corrections department's literature  
review committee, which decided the magazine should be allowed, 
corrections spokesman C.J. Drake said today. 
</P>
<P>
	He said committee members felt the story had no direct bearing  
on Florida's prison system and wasn't particularly inflammatory 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``The article appeared to be stating the facts as opposed to an  
article that would have advocated any course of action,'' Drake 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The story contains Pondexter's account of how he and other  
Corcoran guards abused inmates, including forcing them to fight 
``like gladiators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bonecrusher was part of this gang of guards that was said to  
wager on these fights, part of this gang that shot and killed seven 
of the gladiators when the fights didn't go as planned, or shot and 
killed them just for sport,'' the story says. 
</P>
<P>
	David Granger, Esquire's editor in chief, said before the  
committee's decision he was ``struck that they would find our piece 
so powerful it could cause problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Corcoran, eight officers were indicted for allegedly staging  
gladiator-style fights between inmates. An independent panel found 
last fall that deadly force was not justified in 24 of 31 inmate 
shootings at Corcoran from 1989 to 1995; guards shot some inmates 
engaged in fistfights, killing seven of them. Five others were 
charged with sexually assaulting an inmate. 
</P>
<P>
	Pondexter was never charged and has been granted immunity in  
exchange for his testimony against other guards. He was fired for 
beating up a prisoner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 09:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Golfs With Prince Andrew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
