<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of New York Fires Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                               *and    	
</P>
<P>
                          *CAROLINE BYRNE   	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writers    	
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York, whose accounts are suspected of being used  
for money laundering by Russian mobsters, has fired a London-based 
executive in charge of its Eastern European operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank would not elaborate on its decision to fire the  
executive, Lucy Edwards, but Dow Jones Newswires reported that the 
bank suspected her of misconduct and falsifying records. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Edwards is married to a Russian businessman who serves as a  
director on a company that investigators believe may be associated 
with the scheme. Ms. Edwards was suspended Aug. 18, and her home 
and office were searched by authorities three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	A second executive suspended by the bank, Natasha Kagalovsky,  
has denied wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Edwards could not be reached for comment, and has not been  
charged with any crime. 
</P>
<P>
	In an ironic twist to the case, Ms. Edwards made a presentation  
on the latest money laundering techniques at a conference for 
financial executives in Riga, Latvia, in June. Her speech was 
entitled ``Money Laundering: Latest Developments and Regulations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Gelin, who helped organize the conference for the  
London-based company Shorex Ltd., invited Edwards to address the 
two-day meeting. ``One of her roles at the bank, in terms of taking 
on new clients, was diligence and the money laundering aspects. She 
was trained by the bank in that,'' Gelin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought it would be good to take on someone from a Western  
bank because they were likely to have stricter procedures, more 
than in Eastern Europe,'' Gelin said. ``The Americans are always 
lecturing the world on how fantastic they are, so we trusted 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Money laundering is the process of moving ill-gotten gains  
through a series of bank accounts until they appear like legitimate 
profits from legal businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators suspect that billions of dollars were moved  
through accounts at the Bank of New York, partly through a company 
called Benex Worldwide Ltd. Ms. Edwards' husband, Russian 
businessman Peter Berlin, is listed as a director of Benex. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe the total amount funneled through the bank  
may exceed $10 billion, reports have said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among evidence found by British police during a search of Ms.  
Edwards' London apartment last week was Bank of New York stationery 
with Ms. Edwards' home address on it, according to Dow Jones 
Newswires. Investigators suspect she may have been conducting 
business from her house using the bank's name, according to the 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Federal Bureau of Investigations declined to  
comment. A call to the U.S. Attorney's office in New York, which is 
believed to be investigating the matter, was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The other Bank of New York official suspended pending the  
investigation, Ms. Kagalovsky, is a senior vice president in New 
York who also supervised the bank's business in Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement authorities reportedly are investigating the  
activities of Ms. Kagalovsky's husband Konstantin, who was Russia's 
representative to the International Monetary Fund from 1992 to 1995 
and later worked as a senior executive at Russia's Menetap bank. He 
now is vice president of Russian oil giant Yukos. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple released a statement Thursday denying any wrongdoing  
and dismissing reports of Russian mob involvement as an 
``anti-Russian campaign.'' 









  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 14:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
