<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil: Economic Protest Made Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's leaders acknowledged Friday  
that this week's opposition rally -- the biggest in seven years -- 
had made an impact and that the government had to find ways to 
redirect Brazil's economic goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The peaceful rally Wednesday drew thousands of people from  
around the country to Brasilia, the capital. The protesters came in 
some 2,000 buses to express their discontent with President 
Fernando Henrique Cardoso's belt-tightening free-market reforms, 
which have produced stagnation and high unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the crowd varied from 40,000 to 130,000.  
</P>
<P>
	``This march serves as a reflection, so that these criticisms  
can lead us to a correction of policy,'' said Rep. Inocencio 
Oliveira, a leader of the government-allied Liberal Front Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso also responded, saying ``the message is noted. ... We  
have to look at what lies ahead and what is left to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement with the International Monetary Fund for a  
$41.5 billion loan, Brazil must reduce its budget deficit. But some 
analysts think that in the wake of the protest, the government will 
take a harder line with the IMF, loosening spending restrictions to 
ease the nation's 7.5 percent unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso, who was elected in 1994 and re-elected last year, has  
tried to modernize Brazil's archaic state-run economy. But the 
global crisis that blew up in Asia in 1997 forced the government to 
raise interest rates and devalue its currency, plunging the economy 
into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent poll showed 59 percent of Brazilians think Cardoso is  
doing a bad or terrible job. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition leaders promised to turn up the heat. Next up is the  
``Cry of the Excluded,'' a nationwide protest backed by Brazil's 
Roman Catholic Church and scheduled for Sept. 7, the Brazilian 
Independence Day. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just the beginning,'' said Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva,  
a two-time presidential candidate for the leftist Workers Party. 
``We hope that Cardoso listens and feels the clamor of the 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the protest wasn't all bad news for the government. It was  
smaller than some had feared it would be, and most demonstrators 
were linked to political parties -- very different from the popular 
groundswell that preceded former President Fernando Collor de 
Mello's 1992 impeachment on corruption charges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 15:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
