<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Clesson J. Blaisdell    	
</P>
<P>
	LEBANON, N.H. (AP) -- Clesson J. Blaisdell, president of the New  
Hampshire Senate, died Thursday, a week after suffering a heart 
attack. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democrat from Keene, Blaisdell was in his 15th term in the  
Senate. He was elected Senate president last year after Democrats 
won a Senate majority for the first time since 1912. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Richard C. Freeman    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman, a former  
alderman who served on the federal bench for 28 years and was known 
for his direct approach, died Thursday. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman died Thursday at Piedmont Hospital after suffering  
complications from heart ailments and diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	A Republican, Freeman was nominated by President Nixon and  
confirmed by the Senate in April 1971 to serve in the Northern 
District of Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman served as a member of the Atlanta Board of Aldermen, now  
the City Council, from 1962 to 1971. In 1962, he was named chairman 
of the board's Aviation Committee, which was instrumental in the 
development of Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Tove Hansen    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tove ``Musse'' Hansen, who helped thousands  
of Jews escape the Nazis during World War II, died Saturday. She 
was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hansen, a native of Denmark, helped about 8,000 Danish Jews  
escape to Sweden during the war. Israel later awarded her its 
highest civilian medal. 
</P>
<P>
	She later moved to California and with her husband, Kenneth  
Hansen, built Hollywood's famed Scandia restaurant on Sunset 
Boulevard. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Charles Hollister    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Charles Hollister, who was well-known for his  
research into burying radioactive waste under the ocean, died after 
falling 60 feet while rock climbing in the Big Horn Mountains 
Monday. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollister was vice president and senior scientist at the Woods  
Hole Oceanographic Institution on Cape Cod. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollister was an oceanographer for the U.S. Geological Survey  
and a research fellow at Columbia University's Lamont-Doherty 
Geological Observatory before joining the staff at Woods Hole in 
1967. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a scientist, he pioneered the field of deep-sea sediment  
dynamics, and made us look at mud on the deep sea floor in a 
different way,'' said Robert Gagosian, director of the oceanography 
institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollister also was a past president of the American Alpine Club,  
the nation's oldest mountaineering organization. He participated in 
the first ascent of the 16,860-foot Vinson Massif in the Sentinel 
Range of Antarctica. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Dave Holmes    	
</P>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- Former Hawaii and Eastern Washington  
University football coach Dave Holmes died of an apparent heart 
attack while fly fishing in northern Idaho on Wednesday. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1963 to 1967, Holmes guided Eastern Washington to a 34-13-1  
record, the best winning percentage in school history. At Hawaii 
from 1968 to 1973, his 46-17-1 record also was a school best. 
</P>
<P>
	He resigned after the 1973 season over a dispute with an alumni  
group. He coached at University High School in Spokane before 
retiring about 15 years ago. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Lani Kai    	
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Island entertainer Lani Kai, who had a feature  
role in the Elvis Presley movie ``Blue Hawaii,'' died Tuesday in 
Oahu. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Born George Clarence Dennis James Von Ruckleman Wood III, Kai  
got his break in show business in the 1960s television show 
``Adventures in Paradise,'' playing a crewman aboard the schooner 
``Tiki.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His most famous song, ``Shells,'' was performed by The Surfers.  
Among his other tunes were ``Beautiful Kauai'' and ``Tutu Kane.'' 

</P>
<P>
                        *Chester Brooks Kerr    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW LONDON, N.H. (AP) -- Chester Brooks Kerr, a leading figure in  
book publishing, died Sunday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	During a career spanning 30 years, Kerr worked as the top editor  
or editorial director at Harcourt, Brace &AMP; Co., Yale University 
Press, Atlantic Monthly Press, Reynal &AMP; Hitchcock and Ticknor &AMP; 
Fields, a division of Houghton Mifflin Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his prize acquisitions as a commercial publisher were  
Eugene O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' and Calvin 
Trillin's ``Third Helpings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kerr was best known in the industry for his report on the status  
of scholarly publishing, which became known as the ``Kerr Report.'' 
He concluded that scholarly presses were becoming more like their 
commercial counterparts but never would become self-supporting if 
they concentrated on scholarly quality. 
</P>
<P>
	He graduated from Yale in 1936 and served during World War II as  
chief of the Book Division of the Office of War Information. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Kenneth H. Pearsall    	
</P>
<P>
	NAMPA, Idaho (AP) -- Kenneth H. Pearsall, a former president of  
Northwest Nazarene College, died Wednesday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearsall earned his doctor of divinity degree at Eastern  
Nazarene College in Quincy, Mass., and became the seventh president 
of Northwest Nazarene in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	He resigned in July 1983 to take a similar position at the  
Nazarene Theological College in South Korea. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Raymond Vernon    	
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Raymond Vernon, an internationally  
renowned business expert, died Thursday from complications from 
cancer, according to Harvard University. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Vernon was a member of the Marshall Plan team, and helped  
develop the International Monetary Fund and the General Agreement 
on Tariffs and Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a former head of Hawley and Hoops Inc., a company  
that made the M&AMP;Ms chocolate candies. During his tenure, the 
company successfully developed M&AMP;Ms chocolate-covered peanuts, and 
Vernon was dubbed ``the man who put the crunch in M&AMP;Ms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vernon became a member of the Harvard faculty in 1959. At the  
time of his death, Vernon was the Clarence Dillon professor on 
International Affairs Emeritus at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School 
of Government. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Newell Willcox    	
</P>
<P>
	CORTLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- Newell ``Spiegle'' Willcox, a jazz  
musician who shared the stage with jazz greats including Tommy and 
Jimmy Dorsey and Eddie Lang, died Wednesday. He was 96. 
</P>
<P>
	Willcox grew up in Cortland, where in 1913 he took up the valve  
trombone and joined his father, Lynn, in the town band. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1922, his Ithaca band was discovered by jazz musician Paul  
Whiteman, who renamed the band the Paul Whiteman Collegians and 
brought the group to New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	Willcox remained with the Whiteman group for nearly three years  
before he was asked to replace Tommy Dorsey in the Jean Goldkette 
Orchestra in Detroit. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
