<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Sign Terry Allen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- The New England Patriots signed Terry  
Allen on Friday and got themselves a veteran running back to try 
and replace the injured Robert Edwards and a mentor for rookie 
Kevin Faulk. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, 31, gained 700 yards in 10 games for the Washington  
Redskins last year, averaging 4.7 yards per carry. He has rushed 
for 6,881 yards in his career, sixth among active players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to come here and do whatever they ask me to do,'' Allen  
said. ``To go out, and basically show Kevin what it takes to get 
through the season ... how to prepare for a game. ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have anything to prove to myself,'' he said. ``I've  
been to the Pro Bowl. The only thing I haven't done is win the 
championship and that's what I want to do. ... I think this team 
has what it takes to get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, whose best season was 1996 when he rushed for 1,353 yards  
and was voted to the Pro Bowl, has a history of knee problems of 
his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Drafted by Minnesota in the ninth round out of Clemson in 1990,  
Allen missed his entire rookie season after knee surgery. He also 
missed the 1993 season with a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, 24, ran for 1,115 yards last season as a rookie, but he  
severely injured his knee during a flag football game at the Pro 
Bowl in February. He will miss the entire 1999 season because of 
the injury, which doctors have said could end his career. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots placed running back Derrick Cullors on injured  
reserve after undergoing arthroscopic knee surgery on Wednesday. He 
is expected to miss the entire 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Patriots spokesman Stacey James declined to disclose the terms  
of Allen's contract, but WBZ radio reported that Allen agreed to a 
two-year contract with a $100,000 signing bonus and a $400,000 
annual base salary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990827.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-27 11:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Method of School Violence Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Associated Press poll on school violence is based on  
telephone interviews with 1,016 randomly selected adults from all 
states except Alaska and Hawaii. The interviews were conducted Aug. 
20-25 by ICR of Media, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were weighted to represent the population by  
demographic factors such as age, sex, region and education. 
</P>
<P>
	No more than one time in 20 should chance variations in the  
sample cause the results to vary by more than 3 percentage points 
from the answers that would be obtained if all Americans were 
polled. 
</P>
<P>
	This margin of sampling error is larger for responses of  
subgroups, such as income categories. There are other sources of 
potential error in polls, including the wording and order of 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	1. Which one of the following measures do you think would be the  
most effective way to stop violence in schools? 
</P>
<P>
	--reducing violence in TV shows and movies, 31 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--putting metal detectors in schools, 16 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--increasing counseling for teens, 22 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--passing stricter gun laws, 16 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--restricting Internet content, 5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--don't know/refused, 10 percent  

</P>
<P>
	2. In general, which of the following do you think is the MAIN  
reason kids commit acts of violence? 
</P>
<P>
	--genetic tendencies toward violence, 3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--poor upbringing by parents, 52 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--availability of guns, 8 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--violence in television and movies, 17 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--peer pressure, 17 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--don't know/refused, 3 percent  

</P>
<P>
	3. Do you think installing metal detectors in all schools would  
reduce school violence or not? 
</P>
<P>
	--yes, would, 50 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--no, would not, 47 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--don't know/refused, 3 percent  

</P>
<P>
	4. Do you think stationing police officers in all schools would  
reduce school violence or not? 
</P>
<P>
	--yes ... would, 65 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--no ... would not, 33 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--don't know/refused, 2 percent  

</P>
<P>
	5. In general, do you feel the schools in your community are  
very safe, somewhat safe, not too safe or not safe at all? 
</P>
<P>
	--Very safe, 26 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--somewhat safe, 57 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--not too safe, 9 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--not safe at all, 5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--don't know/refused, 3 percent  
  	   	
