<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Give Back Some Gains / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell for a second straight session  
on Friday, as traders continued to reassess the strong run-up 
earlier in the week and investors steered money into corporate bond 
offerings. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 3/32  
point, or $10.93 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 5.97 percent from 5.90 percent 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices had soared in the past week on expectations that the  
Federal Reserve would let interest rates stabilize for the rest of 
this year. But on Thursday, bond traders began to re-evaluate 
whether yields had fallen too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed on Tuesday raised short-term rates for a second time  
this summer in a pre-emptive strike against inflation. Higher 
interest rates push down prices for bonds, which pay a fixed rate 
of return, but investors had already anticipated the Fed's move. 
Instead, traders focused on hopes that the rate hikes since June 
may be all that is needed to slow down the economy and keep 
inflation at bay for now. But those hopes are now in question. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's largest corporate offering, Fannie Mae, the biggest  
buyer of U.S. mortgages, sold $4 billion of 10- and 30-year 
securities. Additionally, the Federal Home Loan Bank sold $3 
billion of two-year notes. Corporate bond offering hurt Treasurys 
because they usually pay higher interest than government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell 1/8 point to 7/32 point, and intermediate maturities fell 12/32 
point to 23/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.97 percent as the  
discount rose 0.06 percentage point to 4.84 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.10 percent, as the discount rose 0.05 percentage 
point to 4.90 percent. One-year yields were 5.24 percent as the 
discount rose 0.07 percentage point from late Thursday to 4.97 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.25 percent from 5.31 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1/4 point to 114 13/16. The average yield 
to maturity fell to 5.75 percent from 5.76 percent late Thursday. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
