<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Columnist Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A television columnist for The Indianapolis  
Star and The Indianapolis News was suspended and reassigned Friday 
for plagiarizing a story written by a writer at another newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Hall, who has been a television writer at the newspaper  
for 13 years, apologized in a statement posted on the papers' Web 
site Friday night by Executive Editor Frank Caperton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of time pressures, I made a stupid mistake and  
violated a sacred law of our profession,'' he said. ``I apologize 
to our readers and my family, co-workers and friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was suspended without pay for three weeks. When he returns,  
he will be assigned to reporting duties that do not involve writing 
columns, according to Caperton's statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``He also has been warned that if any further lapses in honesty  
come to light he will be dismissed,'' Caperton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone calls by The Associated Press to Caperton and Hall  
were not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was suspended after submitting a story to an editor, who  
noticed that it was strikingly similar to a story done by a 
television writer at another newspaper, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall's story was not published in The Star and The News.  
</P>
<P>
	No details were given about Hall's story, and the other  
newspaper and writer were not identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsroom staffs of the Star and News merged in 1995 and the  
News is due to close Oct. 1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
