<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	State Troopers on Hurricane Alert  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- The governor of North Carolina put state  
troopers on alert and National Guard troops prepared for storm duty 
in South Carolina today as a hurricane watch was posted for 
Florida's eastern coast. Forecasters warned Hurricane Dennis could 
strike the east coast of Florida as soon as tomorrow. At 5 p.m. EDT 
today, Dennis was 315 miles southeast of Cape Canaveral on 
Florida's east coast and 40 miles east-northeast of Harbour Island 
in the Bahamas. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Reverses Voucher Decision  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A federal judge who held up a state-funded  
voucher program just as the school year began reversed himself 
today, allowing some students to attend private schools with 
vouchers this year. U.S. District Judge Solomon Oliver Jr. ruled 
that students who participated in the program for elementary school 
students in Cleveland last year may receive tuition vouchers again 
this year. But those children who are new to the program this year 
will not be allowed to get the tuition grants. 

</P>
<P>
	30 Hurt in Venezuela Clashes  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Police fired water cannons and tear  
gas today to break up clashes between supporters and opponents of 
Venezuela's president outside the country's parliamentary building. 
During the fight, supporters of President Hugo Chavez and the 
National Guard tried to prevent opposition lawmakers from entering 
the Capitol building. Chavez's critics countered with shouts of 
``Democracy!'' and ``No to dictatorship!'' The defiant lawmakers 
broke through the crowd and climbed over the fence. Authorities 
said at least 30 people were injured in the clashes. 

</P>
<P>
	Calif. Gun Controls Signed Into Law  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis tightened California's gun  
controls today, signing into law a ban on the cheapest handguns, 
increased regulations at gun shows and a requirement that trigger 
locks be sold with all guns. With other new laws that expand the 
state's assault weapons ban and limit residents to one gun purchase 
a month, California now has the toughest package of gun control 
laws in the nation, Davis said. 

</P>
<P>
	Beleaguered Mir Crew Undocks  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The last full-time crew undocked from the Mir  
early Saturday, bidding farewell to the 13-year-old Russian space 
station in preparation for its abandonment next year. Next spring, 
the Mir is scheduled to leave outer space and burn up in the 
atmosphere. The crew's departure marked a sad day for the Russian 
space program, a force that put the first satellite in the cosmos, 
as well as the first man and first woman -- and now has no cash, no 
new projects entirely its own and a dim view of the future. 

</P>
<P>
	Teen Accused of IBM Bomb Threat  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An 18-year-old Panamanian admitted he sent  
e-mail bomb threats to IBM, claiming he would demolish the company 
headquarters unless he was paid $5 million, authorities said today. 
Jahair Joel Navarro was charged with threatening to use a weapon of 
mass destruction. The crime, which falls under federal 
anti-terrorism statutes, carries a maximum sentence of life in 
prison without parole. Navarro, a legal resident of the United 
States, was ordered held without bail after prosecutors told a 
judge he had sent a similar threat to Microsoft Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan: Market Has Larger Role  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve needs to pay closer  
attention to what happens on Wall Street, Chairman Alan Greenspan 
said today, since Americans reaping the rewards of the high-flying 
stock market are using those paper profits to justify spending and 
other financial decisions. Some economists interpreted Greenspan's 
comments as a signal that the Fed may further raise interest rates 
this year. Two previous increases -- this week and on June 30 -- have 
not dampened the Wall Street stock-buying ``exuberance'' that 
Greenspan has expressed concern about. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 108.28  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today amid fear that the Fed isn't  
finished raising interest rates. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 108.28 to 
11,090.17. Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
advancers 1,777-1,133. The Nasdaq was down 15.73 at 2,758.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Phenix City in LL WS Final  
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Phenix City, Ala., regrouped after an  
overnight rain delay and rallied today to defeat defending champion 
Toms River, N.J., 3-2 in the U.S. championship game at the Little 
League World Series. Phenix City will play Osaka, Japan, at 4:30 
p.m. tomorrow for the title. Some of Toms River's players, 
including two from last year's team, wept in the dugout as the 
Phenix City squad smothered their pitcher, Bryan Woodall, on the 
pitcher's mound to celebrate. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
















  	   	
</P>
