<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Cutting Ties With Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FALCON HEIGHTS, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura launched an  
attack on the Saint Paul Pioneer Press today on his radio show, 
saying he would cancel subscriptions to the newspaper and not honor 
interview requests. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who repeatedly has singled out the paper for criticism,  
said on the show ``Lunch with the Governor'' that he was upset by 
recent criticism his return to the pro wrestling ring as a referee. 
</P>
<P>
	Editor Walker Lundy wouldn't comment until he has reviewed a  
tape of the show, an assistant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura criticized the paper for its coverage of his guest  
referee appearance at a World Wrestling Federation event Sunday, a 
pay-per-view television show that featured wrestling by scantily 
clad women, vulgar language and simulated violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said the Pioneer Press is hypocritical because it runs  
advertisements for X-rated movies and strip clubs in its sports 
section. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I have to do it by executive order or if I  
simply can state it because I am the governor, but I'm going to 
cancel all subscriptions at the Capitol because I don't want people 
thinking that we at the Capitol in some way support a newspaper 
that supports pornography,'' he said, clarifying that he was 
referring to his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not participate with the Saint Paul Pioneer Porn paper  
anymore, because of the fact that we're going to take a stand on 
this triple-X, this pornography that they're peddling over there,'' 
he said. He said he expected the paper to ``really come after me 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His chief spokesman, John Wodele, said cutting ties with the  
state's second-largest newspaper would not have broader 
ramifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a communications person in the office of the governor, I am  
not concerned with our ability to get our message to the people no 
matter what the circumstances,'' Wodele said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Ventura nor Wodele said how long either moratorium would  
last. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party governor had retired from the ring in 1986  
because of injury. He took part as a WWF referee after a judge 
turned aside legal challenges to his participation. An editorial 
published in the newspaper Tuesday said the governor promoted sex 
and violence during his appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you wonder also what our governor was doing there,  
bringing increased hype and -- no doubt -- more youthful viewers to 
this unredeeming display of behavior?'' the editorial asked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
