<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia/HCA Removing 900 Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Columbia/HCA Healthcare Inc., the  
nation's largest hospital chain, has removed about 900 doctors from 
its payroll as part of a restructuring brought on by a federal 
fraud investigation into the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia, the nation's largest hospital company, once owned  
physician practices that employed 1,500 doctors, but is now 
unraveling many of those contracts. Columbia, like most hospitals, 
lost money owning physician practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Buying physician practices became a popular strategy for  
hospitals in the early 1990s as they sought a way for them tried to 
drive patient admissions. But hospitals largely found when they put 
doctors on salary, the physicians tended to work less and did 
little to boost their practices' revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to stay focused on what you do best. Clearly that  
doesn't mean owning and controlling physicians,'' Columbia senior 
vice president Victor Campbell told The Tennessean on Thursday. 
``We realize that, for us, that's a horrible strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say Columbia still is losing about $100 million a year  
on its doctors and will continue to lose money because it cannot 
simply cancel all the contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell declined to quantify the losses, but said they are  
``substantially less'' than they were two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheryl Skolnick, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens  
in New York, said getting rid of the doctors is a good move. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a Wall Street perspective, it's to be applauded,'' she  
said. ``They might end up with a sleek, profitable company yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said Columbia ``was never an aggressive buyer'' of  
doctors but acquired physician practices in different markets 
depending on its competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The policy was changed after Dr. Thomas Frist took over Columbia  
in 1997. He began a restructuring that has seen the company shrink 
from 344 hospitals to a little more than 200 and get out of the 
home health care business. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Louis Brunsting, a cardiac surgeon at Columbia's Centennial  
Medical Center in Nashville, said he's glad Columbia is focusing on 
running hospitals instead of doctors' practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear that hospitals owning practices has been a failed  
experiment,'' he said. ``I think a hospital's core business is 
providing hospital services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Columbia officials continue negotiations with the  
federal government in an attempt to end the fraud investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, two Columbia middle managers in Florida were  
convicted of defrauding the government by overcharging federal 
health programs. It was the first criminal convictions to stem from 
the investigation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
